WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.449 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.449 --> 00:00:02.415 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:02.415 --> 00:00:04.347 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.347 --> 00:00:05.796 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.796 --> 00:00:10.708 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.708 --> 00:00:12.500 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So last
time we talked about

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:14.070 align:middle line:90%
the Szemerédi-Trotter theorem.

00:00:14.070 --> 00:00:18.380 align:middle line:84%
And today I want to do some
digesting of what we learned.

00:00:18.380 --> 00:00:24.050 align:middle line:84%
So on the one hand, the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem had

00:00:24.050 --> 00:00:27.530 align:middle line:84%
a lot of impact, both the
theorem and the proof.

00:00:27.530 --> 00:00:29.550 align:middle line:90%
And the proof involved topology.

00:00:29.550 --> 00:00:31.760 align:middle line:84%
And that started a whole
thing of using topology

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:33.270 align:middle line:90%
and combinatorics.

00:00:33.270 --> 00:00:36.020 align:middle line:90%
And Tom Wolff learned about it.

00:00:36.020 --> 00:00:38.400 align:middle line:84%
The Fourier analyst Tom
Wolff learned about it.

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:40.280 align:middle line:84%
And he brought the
cell decompositions

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:43.580 align:middle line:84%
and those topological
methods into Fourier analysis

00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:45.180 align:middle line:90%
and had a lot of impact.

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:47.780 align:middle line:84%
And the theorem itself,
the statement is sharp,

00:00:47.780 --> 00:00:49.850 align:middle line:90%
and the proof is fairly short.

00:00:49.850 --> 00:00:50.935 align:middle line:90%
So it's really nice.

00:00:50.935 --> 00:00:53.780 align:middle line:90%


00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:57.500 align:middle line:84%
But there are some questions
that are closely related

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:00.740 align:middle line:84%
to the Szemerédi-Trotter theorem
that the proof doesn't actually

00:01:00.740 --> 00:01:02.510 align:middle line:90%
tell us anything about.

00:01:02.510 --> 00:01:07.520 align:middle line:84%
And so I wanted to go through
them today and discuss

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:09.590 align:middle line:84%
why the proof doesn't
tell us much about some

00:01:09.590 --> 00:01:10.890 align:middle line:90%
of these related things.

00:01:10.890 --> 00:01:13.490 align:middle line:84%
And some of those things
will be the main topics

00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:16.910 align:middle line:90%
of the class going forward.

00:01:16.910 --> 00:01:17.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:25.400 align:middle line:84%
So, I'm going to put on the
board Szemerédi-Trotter theorem

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:28.776 align:middle line:90%
and proof are quite remarkable.

00:01:28.776 --> 00:01:34.070 align:middle line:90%


00:01:34.070 --> 00:01:43.520 align:middle line:84%
But they don't tell us anything
about some questions that

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:45.860 align:middle line:90%
seem closely related.

00:01:45.860 --> 00:01:47.102 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:47.102 --> 00:01:52.310 align:middle line:84%
So number one, doesn't tell us
anything about projection theory

00:01:52.310 --> 00:01:53.455 align:middle line:90%
in finite fields.

00:01:53.455 --> 00:01:58.790 align:middle line:90%


00:01:58.790 --> 00:02:00.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:05.030 align:middle line:84%
Number two, it doesn't tell us
anything about the structure

00:02:05.030 --> 00:02:05.943 align:middle line:90%
of sharp examples.

00:02:05.943 --> 00:02:17.720 align:middle line:90%


00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:19.040 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:02:19.040 --> 00:02:21.420 align:middle line:84%
So we discussed a
little bit last class.

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:23.810 align:middle line:84%
I mentioned the sharp examples
for the Szemerédi-Trotter

00:02:23.810 --> 00:02:25.670 align:middle line:90%
theorem that we know.

00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:27.960 align:middle line:84%
And it's an
interesting question.

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:30.770 align:middle line:84%
If you have an example that
is close to being sharp

00:02:30.770 --> 00:02:32.310 align:middle line:84%
for the Szemerédi-Trotter
theorem,

00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:35.180 align:middle line:84%
can we say anything
about its structure?

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:37.650 align:middle line:84%
And it might be a
little surprising,

00:02:37.650 --> 00:02:40.070 align:middle line:84%
but the proof of the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem really

00:02:40.070 --> 00:02:42.260 align:middle line:90%
gives no information about that.

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:44.720 align:middle line:90%
And we'll talk about why.

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:45.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:45.350 --> 00:02:47.000 align:middle line:90%
Number three.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.260 align:middle line:84%
So the Szemerédi-Trotter theorem
is the sharp theorem about

00:02:51.260 --> 00:02:56.760 align:middle line:84%
projection theory for sets of
points in the Euclidean plane

00:02:56.760 --> 00:02:59.370 align:middle line:90%
in R2, finite sets in R2.

00:02:59.370 --> 00:03:01.110 align:middle line:84%
So you might hope
that it would tell you

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:04.860 align:middle line:84%
something helpful about
projection theory for sets

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:07.590 align:middle line:90%
of unit balls in R2.

00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:09.940 align:middle line:84%
But it says rather
little about that.

00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:12.870 align:middle line:84%
So it says rather little
about the projection

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:25.440 align:middle line:84%
theory of unit balls in R2
with some spatial conditions.

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:28.383 align:middle line:84%
So I'll put here with
the Hausdorff spacing.

00:03:28.383 --> 00:03:32.700 align:middle line:90%


00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:35.170 align:middle line:84%
So this is also a
little bit surprising.

00:03:35.170 --> 00:03:39.720 align:middle line:84%
And so Tom Wolff was really
interested in analysis problems,

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:41.320 align:middle line:90%
problems like this.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.160 align:middle line:84%
And he found the
Szemerédi-Trotter proof

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:47.010 align:middle line:84%
in the combinatorics literature,
which at that time were like two

00:03:47.010 --> 00:03:49.620 align:middle line:84%
pretty different groups
of mathematicians.

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:52.920 align:middle line:84%
And he imported it, and he tried
to use it to answer questions

00:03:52.920 --> 00:03:53.890 align:middle line:90%
like this.

00:03:53.890 --> 00:03:56.140 align:middle line:84%
And he did prove a bunch
of interesting stuff,

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:59.280 align:middle line:84%
but he was not able to
answer this question.

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:02.490 align:middle line:84%
And so we'll talk about
what the issue is,

00:04:02.490 --> 00:04:06.690 align:middle line:84%
why the Szemerédi-Trotter proof
does not say all that much about

00:04:06.690 --> 00:04:09.330 align:middle line:90%
this set.

00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:10.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:11.370 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:16.410 align:middle line:84%
And then going forward,
this and this, maybe this

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:18.785 align:middle line:84%
are going to be some of the
main topics of our class.

00:04:18.785 --> 00:04:22.440 align:middle line:90%


00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:23.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:23.830 align:middle line:90%
Oh yeah.

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:28.260 align:middle line:84%
And so let me also mention one
of the big developments that

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:30.720 align:middle line:84%
made me excited to teach the
class is that there is now

00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:33.900 align:middle line:84%
a sharp theorem about this
proven by Orponen and Shmerkin

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:38.820 align:middle line:84%
and Ren and Wang, and actually
doesn't use any of the methods

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:41.490 align:middle line:84%
from the
Szemerédi-Trotter proof.

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:45.330 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so we'll talk
today to explain why

00:04:45.330 --> 00:04:47.530 align:middle line:90%
something different is needed.

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:49.620 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll meet
the something different

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:53.220 align:middle line:90%
starting next class.

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:54.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:55.420 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:04:55.420 --> 00:04:59.490 align:middle line:84%
So why does the method
that we saw-- yeah?

00:04:59.490 --> 00:05:01.050 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Are there
any other spaces

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:04.980 align:middle line:84%
other than real space
where a similar--

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:07.200 align:middle line:84%
not actually the
technical wheels,

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:10.080 align:middle line:90%
plates, but in other words?

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:12.538 align:middle line:84%
I know that it doesn't just
move over a finite [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:12.538 --> 00:05:15.247 align:middle line:84%
Is there anything that's kind of
similar enough to the real thing

00:05:15.247 --> 00:05:15.930 align:middle line:90%
before?

00:05:15.930 --> 00:05:16.763 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:05:16.763 --> 00:05:20.700 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the question is the key
ingredient in the proof we did

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:23.480 align:middle line:84%
of the Szemerédi-Trotter theorem
is this cell decomposition

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:23.980 align:middle line:90%
lemma.

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:26.680 align:middle line:84%
You can cut the plane
up into pieces in a way

00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:29.050 align:middle line:84%
so that each line doesn't
go through too many pieces.

00:05:29.050 --> 00:05:30.972 align:middle line:84%
And the question
was, other than R2,

00:05:30.972 --> 00:05:33.180 align:middle line:84%
are there some other spaces
where something like this

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:34.735 align:middle line:90%
would work?

00:05:34.735 --> 00:05:35.235 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:35.235 --> 00:05:37.680 align:middle line:84%
So it works, at
least to some extent,

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:40.500 align:middle line:90%
in higher dimensions, Rn.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:43.950 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't make any
sense over Fp, which as I

00:05:43.950 --> 00:05:45.450 align:middle line:90%
was going to say in a second.

00:05:45.450 --> 00:05:51.450 align:middle line:84%
And it works with some
modifications in Cn.

00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:56.940 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, and those are
all the spaces, really,

00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:57.860 align:middle line:90%
I know where it works.

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:00.690 align:middle line:90%


00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:02.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:02.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:02.590 --> 00:06:05.220 align:middle line:90%
So we just mentioned.

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:07.810 align:middle line:84%
So why did these methods
not work over Fp?

00:06:07.810 --> 00:06:12.400 align:middle line:84%
Well, we had this basic thing
of cutting a space into pieces

00:06:12.400 --> 00:06:14.025 align:middle line:84%
where the simplest
thing would be like,

00:06:14.025 --> 00:06:15.870 align:middle line:84%
you take a line in the
plane and it cuts it

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:18.030 align:middle line:90%
into two connected components.

00:06:18.030 --> 00:06:22.900 align:middle line:84%
And that just doesn't
make sense in Fp2.

00:06:22.900 --> 00:06:24.960 align:middle line:84%
If you remove a line
from Fp2, there's

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:26.430 align:middle line:84%
no sense in which
what's left over

00:06:26.430 --> 00:06:30.000 align:middle line:84%
is organized into
two components.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:30.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:30.610 --> 00:06:32.910 align:middle line:84%
So this one is not
that surprising.

00:06:32.910 --> 00:06:34.630 align:middle line:84%
And these are a little
more surprising.

00:06:34.630 --> 00:06:37.050 align:middle line:84%
And we think we need to
talk in some more depth

00:06:37.050 --> 00:06:41.110 align:middle line:84%
to explain why we didn't
learn anything about them.

00:06:41.110 --> 00:06:41.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:41.610 --> 00:06:47.390 align:middle line:90%


00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:47.890 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:06:47.890 --> 00:06:51.450 align:middle line:84%
So first we'll talk about the
structure of sharp examples

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:52.780 align:middle line:90%
for the ST theorem.

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:55.660 align:middle line:84%
And let me first remind you
what the ST theorem says,

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:57.900 align:middle line:90%
and what are the sharp examples.

00:06:57.900 --> 00:07:01.630 align:middle line:90%
So the theorem was this.

00:07:01.630 --> 00:07:06.780 align:middle line:84%
So I have a set X is a set
of points in the plane,

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:10.440 align:middle line:84%
and L is the set of
lines in the plane.

00:07:10.440 --> 00:07:13.330 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to count
the incidences between them.

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:16.830 align:middle line:84%
The theorem says that the number
of incidences between X and L

00:07:16.830 --> 00:07:20.170 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by the number of
points plus the number of lines,

00:07:20.170 --> 00:07:22.070 align:middle line:90%
plus a more complicated term.

00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:25.170 align:middle line:90%


00:07:25.170 --> 00:07:31.020 align:middle line:84%
And I will just label these
terms I and II and III.

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:31.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:39.430 align:middle line:84%
So the situation where term I
dominates is easy to imagine.

00:07:39.430 --> 00:07:41.500 align:middle line:84%
We just need to put
each point on a line.

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:43.570 align:middle line:90%
So I'll draw some lines.

00:07:43.570 --> 00:07:46.460 align:middle line:84%
And then each point I will
put on one of these lines.

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:50.260 align:middle line:90%


00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:50.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:54.580 align:middle line:84%
So this type of example I
would describe as not having

00:07:54.580 --> 00:07:56.680 align:middle line:90%
any remarkable structure.

00:07:56.680 --> 00:07:59.330 align:middle line:90%
So this is not rigid.

00:07:59.330 --> 00:08:03.010 align:middle line:84%
And there are many
degrees of freedom.

00:08:03.010 --> 00:08:05.865 align:middle line:84%
So I would say no
special structure here.

00:08:05.865 --> 00:08:11.230 align:middle line:90%


00:08:11.230 --> 00:08:12.090 align:middle line:90%
It's not rigid.

00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:15.473 align:middle line:90%


00:08:15.473 --> 00:08:16.890 align:middle line:84%
There are many
degrees of freedom.

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:22.360 align:middle line:90%


00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:25.220 align:middle line:84%
Each one of these points I can
slide freely along this line.

00:08:25.220 --> 00:08:28.570 align:middle line:84%
So I have at least X
degrees of freedom.

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:29.440 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:30.920 align:middle line:90%
Now, example.

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:33.760 align:middle line:84%
The situation
where II dominates,

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:36.520 align:middle line:84%
the picture is a little bit
different but it's similar.

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:41.559 align:middle line:84%
So to have L incidences,
I just need that each line

00:08:41.559 --> 00:08:43.090 align:middle line:90%
goes through a point.

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:44.650 align:middle line:90%
So there's a few points.

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:45.590 align:middle line:90%
I put them anywhere.

00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:47.090 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm going
to draw my lines,

00:08:47.090 --> 00:08:49.310 align:middle line:84%
and each line will go
through one of these points.

00:08:49.310 --> 00:08:51.015 align:middle line:90%
So it just looks like-- whoops.

00:08:51.015 --> 00:08:54.370 align:middle line:90%


00:08:54.370 --> 00:08:56.020 align:middle line:90%
Looks like that.

00:08:56.020 --> 00:08:59.200 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes called
the stars example.

00:08:59.200 --> 00:08:59.810 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:59.810 --> 00:09:02.420 align:middle line:84%
And again, there's
no special structure.

00:09:02.420 --> 00:09:03.363 align:middle line:90%
It's not rigid.

00:09:03.363 --> 00:09:04.780 align:middle line:84%
There are many
degrees of freedom.

00:09:04.780 --> 00:09:08.660 align:middle line:84%
I can rotate this
line, and so on.

00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:09.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:09.160 --> 00:09:13.210 align:middle line:84%
And then example III,
when this term dominates,

00:09:13.210 --> 00:09:15.850 align:middle line:84%
those are harder to come by,
and they have more structure,

00:09:15.850 --> 00:09:17.210 align:middle line:90%
and they're more interesting.

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:24.585 align:middle line:84%
So the known examples
are an integer grid.

00:09:24.585 --> 00:09:27.100 align:middle line:90%


00:09:27.100 --> 00:09:30.520 align:middle line:90%
Integer grid.

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:34.510 align:middle line:84%
Or instead of the integers,
you could take a ring,

00:09:34.510 --> 00:09:36.920 align:middle line:90%
like a ring in a number field.

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:39.130 align:middle line:90%
This kind of grid.

00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:42.550 align:middle line:84%
Or more generally, you
could take an R grid

00:09:42.550 --> 00:09:49.935 align:middle line:84%
where R is the ring of
integers in a number field.

00:09:49.935 --> 00:09:55.870 align:middle line:90%


00:09:55.870 --> 00:09:57.727 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:57.727 --> 00:09:58.935 align:middle line:90%
Let me draw a little picture.

00:09:58.935 --> 00:10:04.420 align:middle line:90%


00:10:04.420 --> 00:10:05.150 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:07.060 align:middle line:84%
So this is the scenario
where the known

00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:10.270 align:middle line:90%
examples have structure.

00:10:10.270 --> 00:10:14.483 align:middle line:84%
So we have structure
in the known examples.

00:10:14.483 --> 00:10:19.630 align:middle line:90%


00:10:19.630 --> 00:10:22.060 align:middle line:84%
And we have very few
degrees of freedom

00:10:22.060 --> 00:10:23.603 align:middle line:90%
to perturb these examples.

00:10:23.603 --> 00:10:26.680 align:middle line:90%


00:10:26.680 --> 00:10:27.430 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:10:27.430 --> 00:10:28.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:29.830 align:middle line:84%
Are there any
questions or comments?

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:30.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:35.180 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If you embed R2 into
the real projective plane,

00:10:35.180 --> 00:10:39.070 align:middle line:84%
there's a duality that takes
lines in the real projective

00:10:39.070 --> 00:10:42.490 align:middle line:84%
plane to points and
switches points with lines

00:10:42.490 --> 00:10:44.950 align:middle line:90%
and it preserves intersections.

00:10:44.950 --> 00:10:48.580 align:middle line:84%
And it seems to me like the
first two classes of example

00:10:48.580 --> 00:10:50.410 align:middle line:84%
are kind of dual
when you do that.

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:53.080 align:middle line:84%
Is the third class
of examples like,

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:58.637 align:middle line:84%
self-dual if you do that kind
of switching lines and points?

00:10:58.637 --> 00:10:59.470 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:10:59.470 --> 00:11:00.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:01.430 align:middle line:90%
That's a great question.

00:11:01.430 --> 00:11:02.930 align:middle line:84%
Let me just repeat
it for everybody.

00:11:02.930 --> 00:11:07.620 align:middle line:84%
So there's a structure
called point-line duality.

00:11:07.620 --> 00:11:08.120 align:middle line:90%
So.

00:11:08.120 --> 00:11:15.760 align:middle line:90%


00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:17.980 align:middle line:84%
That's probably
nicest to explain it

00:11:17.980 --> 00:11:22.700 align:middle line:90%
in the projector space.

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:25.520 align:middle line:84%
But let me say it
in a lowbrow way.

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:27.760 align:middle line:84%
So if I have a line
y, I can probably

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:32.506 align:middle line:90%
write it as y equals mx plus b.

00:11:32.506 --> 00:11:37.670 align:middle line:84%
In other words-- and let me do
this is a little [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:37.670 --> 00:11:40.300 align:middle line:84%
but I'm going to write
it as mx minus b.

00:11:40.300 --> 00:11:41.060 align:middle line:90%
Why not?

00:11:41.060 --> 00:11:48.310 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, the line is
0 equals mx minus b minus y.

00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:55.204 align:middle line:84%
So if I have a set of points,
it would be x1, y1, xN, yN.

00:11:55.204 --> 00:11:56.830 align:middle line:90%
Just add Points.

00:11:56.830 --> 00:12:07.150 align:middle line:84%
If I have a set of lines, they
might be m1, b1, and then mL bL

00:12:07.150 --> 00:12:08.010 align:middle line:90%
if I had L lines.

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:11.020 align:middle line:90%


00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:13.490 align:middle line:84%
And if I want to
count incidences,

00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:15.650 align:middle line:84%
I consider a different
point, different line,

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:17.680 align:middle line:90%
and I check this equation.

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:20.870 align:middle line:84%
And this equation is
actually symmetric

00:12:20.870 --> 00:12:25.090 align:middle line:84%
if you switch the role
of mb and the role of xy.

00:12:25.090 --> 00:12:27.850 align:middle line:90%


00:12:27.850 --> 00:12:31.240 align:middle line:84%
So I can turn my
points into lines

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:34.060 align:middle line:90%
and turn my lines into points.

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:42.370 align:middle line:84%
So this is a symmetric if I
take mb and switch it with xy.

00:12:42.370 --> 00:12:45.300 align:middle line:90%


00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:50.060 align:middle line:84%
So as a student pointed out,
if you take this example,

00:12:50.060 --> 00:12:53.960 align:middle line:84%
and then you apply point-line
duality, you get this example.

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:56.680 align:middle line:84%
So this line here
became that point.

00:12:56.680 --> 00:12:59.600 align:middle line:90%
These points became those lines.

00:12:59.600 --> 00:13:00.580 align:middle line:90%
And so on.

00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:03.910 align:middle line:84%
So these two examples
are dual to each other.

00:13:03.910 --> 00:13:04.550 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:13:04.550 --> 00:13:08.290 align:middle line:84%
Now the question was,
if you take this example

00:13:08.290 --> 00:13:13.660 align:middle line:84%
and you apply point-line
duality, what do you get?

00:13:13.660 --> 00:13:17.740 align:middle line:84%
And you actually do get
something different.

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:27.153 align:middle line:84%
So you can apply
point-line duality.

00:13:27.153 --> 00:13:31.185 align:middle line:90%


00:13:31.185 --> 00:13:32.140 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:13:32.140 --> 00:13:34.990 align:middle line:84%
So to think about what would
happen if we did this--

00:13:34.990 --> 00:13:36.670 align:middle line:84%
I won't do it in
complete detail,

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:39.260 align:middle line:90%
but let's take a first step.

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:43.620 align:middle line:84%
So when I do that, each one of
these lines will become a point,

00:13:43.620 --> 00:13:47.400 align:middle line:84%
and the point will
be labeled like mb.

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:52.040 align:middle line:84%
So the x-coordinate of our
point will be the slope.

00:13:52.040 --> 00:13:54.240 align:middle line:84%
So who are the slopes
of these lines?

00:13:54.240 --> 00:13:56.100 align:middle line:90%
Well, we constructed them.

00:13:56.100 --> 00:13:59.640 align:middle line:84%
The slopes were rational
numbers with small denominators.

00:13:59.640 --> 00:14:01.290 align:middle line:84%
So those will be
the x-coordinates.

00:14:01.290 --> 00:14:03.740 align:middle line:84%
They'll be rational numbers
with small denominators.

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:07.010 align:middle line:84%
And then for each
x-coordinate, the y-coordinates

00:14:07.010 --> 00:14:08.610 align:middle line:90%
will be the different b values.

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:11.970 align:middle line:84%
So the different places
where it hits the y-axis.

00:14:11.970 --> 00:14:15.500 align:middle line:84%
And you can compute
that with a little work.

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:18.110 align:middle line:84%
And you get a set, which
is not a grid, actually.

00:14:18.110 --> 00:14:19.620 align:middle line:90%
It's not an integer grid.

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:22.430 align:middle line:84%
So the set of rationals
with small denominators,

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:32.270 align:middle line:84%
that's not integer
multiples of one number.

00:14:32.270 --> 00:14:35.000 align:middle line:84%
So it is actually a
genuinely different example

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.790 align:middle line:84%
when you switch the
points and the lines.

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:38.510 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:39.700 align:middle line:90%
So that's great.

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:41.450 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing
we mentioned last time

00:14:41.450 --> 00:14:44.130 align:middle line:84%
is that you can apply
projective transformations.

00:14:44.130 --> 00:14:50.270 align:middle line:90%


00:14:50.270 --> 00:14:52.495 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:52.495 --> 00:14:55.620 align:middle line:84%
So this list of examples
is a little bit messy.

00:14:55.620 --> 00:14:57.930 align:middle line:84%
There are few of them, but
it's a little bit messy,

00:14:57.930 --> 00:15:00.680 align:middle line:84%
and that perhaps has
contributed to making

00:15:00.680 --> 00:15:03.080 align:middle line:84%
it feel daunting to prove
that all of the examples

00:15:03.080 --> 00:15:04.105 align:middle line:90%
look like one of these.

00:15:04.105 --> 00:15:07.430 align:middle line:90%


00:15:07.430 --> 00:15:08.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:08.130 --> 00:15:09.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, great.

00:15:09.830 --> 00:15:10.675 align:middle line:90%
Great question.

00:15:10.675 --> 00:15:14.930 align:middle line:90%


00:15:14.930 --> 00:15:16.880 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:20.660 align:middle line:84%
So next, I thought that we
would go over a bit the proof

00:15:20.660 --> 00:15:24.950 align:middle line:84%
of the Szemerédi-Trotter theorem
with an eye towards what does it

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:27.680 align:middle line:84%
tell us about the structure
of sharp examples.

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:30.120 align:middle line:84%
And unfortunately, we'll
see it tells us very little.

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:31.645 align:middle line:90%
But it's good to see it.

00:15:31.645 --> 00:15:44.960 align:middle line:90%


00:15:44.960 --> 00:15:46.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:50.815 align:middle line:84%
So the first step in the proof
was a double counting argument.

00:15:50.815 --> 00:15:54.920 align:middle line:90%


00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:57.590 align:middle line:84%
And a double counting argument
proved a weaker upper bound

00:15:57.590 --> 00:16:00.340 align:middle line:84%
for the number of
incidences, which was this.

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:04.670 align:middle line:90%


00:16:04.670 --> 00:16:06.650 align:middle line:84%
And that double
counting argument

00:16:06.650 --> 00:16:09.240 align:middle line:84%
has a corollary, which
is perhaps easier to say.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:11.750 align:middle line:84%
And the corollary is actually
the only thing you really need

00:16:11.750 --> 00:16:14.360 align:middle line:84%
to prove the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:18.140 align:middle line:84%
The corollary says that
if the number of lines

00:16:18.140 --> 00:16:20.210 align:middle line:84%
is more than the
number of points

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:24.590 align:middle line:84%
squared, then the
number of incidences

00:16:24.590 --> 00:16:30.630 align:middle line:84%
is just bounded by the number of
lines, which is, in other words,

00:16:30.630 --> 00:16:32.870 align:middle line:84%
it matches the
case II over here.

00:16:32.870 --> 00:16:35.493 align:middle line:84%
The picture looks like this,
where a typical line just

00:16:35.493 --> 00:16:36.785 align:middle line:90%
goes through one of the points.

00:16:36.785 --> 00:16:39.750 align:middle line:90%


00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:41.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:43.380 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:45.430 align:middle line:84%
So actually, I didn't
emphasize that last time,

00:16:45.430 --> 00:16:48.240 align:middle line:84%
but that's a nice thing to say
because this corollary is maybe

00:16:48.240 --> 00:16:52.290 align:middle line:84%
easier to hold in our mind
than whatever the exponents are

00:16:52.290 --> 00:16:54.900 align:middle line:90%
up there.

00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:56.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:56.010 --> 00:16:59.960 align:middle line:84%
So now the next idea was
this cell decomposition idea.

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:04.140 align:middle line:90%


00:17:04.140 --> 00:17:07.230 align:middle line:84%
So let me draw an example
for Szemerédi-Trotter,

00:17:07.230 --> 00:17:09.310 align:middle line:84%
and then I'll draw the
cell decomposition,

00:17:09.310 --> 00:17:11.045 align:middle line:84%
and we'll talk about
how it's helping us.

00:17:11.045 --> 00:17:17.910 align:middle line:90%


00:17:17.910 --> 00:17:20.859 align:middle line:84%
So I'll have a set
of points like that.

00:17:20.859 --> 00:17:22.660 align:middle line:90%
It might be an integer grid.

00:17:22.660 --> 00:17:24.440 align:middle line:90%
And then I have some lines here.

00:17:24.440 --> 00:17:32.600 align:middle line:90%


00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:34.970 align:middle line:90%
Lines at those slopes.

00:17:34.970 --> 00:17:35.963 align:middle line:90%
Lines at these slopes.

00:17:35.963 --> 00:17:41.445 align:middle line:90%


00:17:41.445 --> 00:17:41.945 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:41.945 --> 00:17:45.260 align:middle line:90%
Et cetera.

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:48.990 align:middle line:84%
And then we will do
a cell decomposition.

00:17:48.990 --> 00:17:56.660 align:middle line:90%


00:17:56.660 --> 00:17:58.160 align:middle line:90%
Those are our cells.

00:17:58.160 --> 00:17:59.300 align:middle line:90%
So our cell wall.

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:03.860 align:middle line:90%
And here are our cells O sub i.

00:18:03.860 --> 00:18:05.985 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:05.985 --> 00:18:13.880 align:middle line:84%
So let's say Xi is X
intersected with Oi,

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:20.285 align:middle line:84%
and Li is the set of lines
so that L intersect Oy is not

00:18:20.285 --> 00:18:20.785 align:middle line:90%
empty.

00:18:20.785 --> 00:18:26.690 align:middle line:90%


00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:28.995 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:28.995 --> 00:18:35.010 align:middle line:84%
And what we can do with
the cell decomposition

00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:40.380 align:middle line:84%
is that we choose our cell
decomposition fine enough.

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:45.540 align:middle line:84%
So the cell decomposition
has a parameter S.

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:52.080 align:middle line:84%
There's a parameter S. And
in terms of this parameter,

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:56.790 align:middle line:90%
Xi is like X over S squared.

00:18:56.790 --> 00:18:59.260 align:middle line:84%
So you can think of there
being S squared cells,

00:18:59.260 --> 00:19:01.770 align:middle line:84%
and the points are
distributed evenly among them.

00:19:01.770 --> 00:19:09.730 align:middle line:84%
And Li is at most X over
S. And in sharp examples,

00:19:09.730 --> 00:19:13.320 align:middle line:90%
this would be an equality.

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:14.562 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:14.562 --> 00:19:19.260 align:middle line:84%
So what we do is we do the
cell decomposition fine

00:19:19.260 --> 00:19:26.500 align:middle line:84%
enough so that Li is
bigger than Xi squared.

00:19:26.500 --> 00:19:28.270 align:middle line:90%
And then we use the corollary.

00:19:28.270 --> 00:19:37.015 align:middle line:90%


00:19:37.015 --> 00:19:37.515 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:37.515 --> 00:19:48.120 align:middle line:90%


00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:48.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:52.080 align:middle line:84%
So why does this not
help us very much?

00:19:52.080 --> 00:19:55.560 align:middle line:84%
Why does this not help very much
to understand the structure?

00:19:55.560 --> 00:19:59.702 align:middle line:84%
So what we've done here
is we've cut our original,

00:19:59.702 --> 00:20:01.410 align:middle line:84%
we've cut our space
into cells, and we're

00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:03.280 align:middle line:84%
going to look one
cell at a time.

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:08.160 align:middle line:84%
In each cell, we see a ton of
lines and not that many points.

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:12.750 align:middle line:84%
And then by double counting, we
can deduce that in each cell,

00:20:12.750 --> 00:20:15.480 align:middle line:90%
we have this bound.

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:17.460 align:middle line:84%
So we use our
corollary that says

00:20:17.460 --> 00:20:22.050 align:middle line:84%
that the number of
incidences between Xi and Li

00:20:22.050 --> 00:20:23.460 align:middle line:90%
is at most around Li.

00:20:23.460 --> 00:20:26.040 align:middle line:90%


00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:30.240 align:middle line:84%
So within each
cell, a typical line

00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:32.470 align:middle line:84%
is only hitting one
point within the cell.

00:20:32.470 --> 00:20:35.340 align:middle line:90%


00:20:35.340 --> 00:20:37.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:40.420 align:middle line:84%
So this divide and
conquer argument,

00:20:40.420 --> 00:20:42.730 align:middle line:84%
we're cutting space
up into cells,

00:20:42.730 --> 00:20:44.890 align:middle line:84%
and then we're thinking
about them one at a time.

00:20:44.890 --> 00:20:49.740 align:middle line:84%
And doing that simplifies our
life because we have broken

00:20:49.740 --> 00:20:51.160 align:middle line:84%
our problem into
smaller problems,

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:53.490 align:middle line:84%
and we just think about
them one at a time.

00:20:53.490 --> 00:20:55.440 align:middle line:84%
And we understand
each smaller problem

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:58.680 align:middle line:84%
well enough to bound the
total number of incidences.

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:04.080 align:middle line:84%
But we are not paying attention
to any possible interaction

00:21:04.080 --> 00:21:06.870 align:middle line:90%
between these cells.

00:21:06.870 --> 00:21:09.930 align:middle line:84%
And the structure is all
about the interaction

00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:12.900 align:middle line:90%
between the cells.

00:21:12.900 --> 00:21:25.470 align:middle line:84%
So a given line in
our story is actually

00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:27.700 align:middle line:84%
appearing in many
different cells.

00:21:27.700 --> 00:21:30.810 align:middle line:84%
And so there's some
relationship between what's

00:21:30.810 --> 00:21:33.460 align:middle line:84%
going on in this cell and
what's going on in that cell.

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:36.840 align:middle line:84%
And in our proof, we're not
trying to understand or exploit

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:37.780 align:middle line:90%
that relationship.

00:21:37.780 --> 00:21:41.490 align:middle line:84%
We're just looking at
the cells one at a time.

00:21:41.490 --> 00:21:42.160 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:43.740 align:middle line:84%
So the only structure
that the proof

00:21:43.740 --> 00:21:47.280 align:middle line:84%
gives us is that within each
cell, you see some points,

00:21:47.280 --> 00:21:52.140 align:middle line:84%
and you see some lines, and
each line only goes through one

00:21:52.140 --> 00:21:54.930 align:middle line:84%
point within the
cell, which is not yet

00:21:54.930 --> 00:21:57.120 align:middle line:90%
a rigid structure at all.

00:21:57.120 --> 00:21:58.775 align:middle line:84%
And that's all that
the proof gives us.

00:21:58.775 --> 00:22:07.530 align:middle line:90%


00:22:07.530 --> 00:22:09.650 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or
comments about that?

00:22:09.650 --> 00:22:18.090 align:middle line:90%


00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:20.160 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:22.920 align:middle line:84%
So I have been wondering
about this question

00:22:22.920 --> 00:22:26.110 align:middle line:90%
of structure of sharp examples.

00:22:26.110 --> 00:22:31.960 align:middle line:84%
And I thought of a direction
that people are interested,

00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:33.940 align:middle line:84%
people could pursue
as a project.

00:22:33.940 --> 00:22:35.410 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to
put it out there.

00:22:35.410 --> 00:22:37.500 align:middle line:84%
So take 10 or 15 minutes
to share a project

00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:43.290 align:middle line:84%
idea of some smaller
problems that might build up

00:22:43.290 --> 00:22:44.510 align:middle line:90%
towards understanding this.

00:22:44.510 --> 00:22:47.220 align:middle line:90%


00:22:47.220 --> 00:22:50.370 align:middle line:90%
So here was my thought.

00:22:50.370 --> 00:22:55.680 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, this
general incidence theorem

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:57.790 align:middle line:90%
implies a projection theorem.

00:22:57.790 --> 00:22:59.595 align:middle line:84%
The projection theorem
is more specialized.

00:22:59.595 --> 00:23:02.220 align:middle line:84%
And I think it might be easier
to understand the sharp examples

00:23:02.220 --> 00:23:03.345 align:middle line:90%
for the projection theorem.

00:23:03.345 --> 00:23:14.970 align:middle line:90%


00:23:14.970 --> 00:23:15.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:18.430 align:middle line:84%
So I called it a
theorem last time.

00:23:18.430 --> 00:23:20.430 align:middle line:84%
We could also call
it a corollary.

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:25.570 align:middle line:84%
So X is contained in
R2 as a finite set.

00:23:25.570 --> 00:23:27.376 align:middle line:90%
D is a set of directions.

00:23:27.376 --> 00:23:33.460 align:middle line:90%


00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:40.360 align:middle line:84%
And then S of XD is
the maximum over all

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:44.770 align:middle line:84%
of the directions of the
size of pi theta of X.

00:23:44.770 --> 00:23:47.740 align:middle line:84%
And the way I've
stated the theorem

00:23:47.740 --> 00:23:51.310 align:middle line:84%
before is that the number
of directions is at most 1

00:23:51.310 --> 00:23:56.410 align:middle line:84%
plus S squared over the number
of points, but algebraically,

00:23:56.410 --> 00:23:58.690 align:middle line:84%
it's equivalent to say
the following thing.

00:23:58.690 --> 00:24:01.820 align:middle line:84%
If the number of
directions is at least 2,

00:24:01.820 --> 00:24:08.362 align:middle line:84%
then S is at least X to
the 1/2 D to the 1/2.

00:24:08.362 --> 00:24:09.195 align:middle line:90%
That's just algebra.

00:24:09.195 --> 00:24:12.488 align:middle line:90%


00:24:12.488 --> 00:24:14.530 align:middle line:84%
The case where the number
of directions is just 1

00:24:14.530 --> 00:24:15.590 align:middle line:90%
is not very interesting.

00:24:15.590 --> 00:24:17.540 align:middle line:84%
If you're only projecting
in one direction,

00:24:17.540 --> 00:24:20.475 align:middle line:84%
it could easily happen that the
projection has only one point.

00:24:20.475 --> 00:24:25.766 align:middle line:90%


00:24:25.766 --> 00:24:26.266 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:26.266 --> 00:24:29.914 align:middle line:90%


00:24:29.914 --> 00:24:33.670 align:middle line:84%
So this is a very
special case of this.

00:24:33.670 --> 00:24:35.900 align:middle line:84%
In this case, what
are the lines?

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:38.290 align:middle line:84%
The set of lines are
all of the lines that

00:24:38.290 --> 00:24:41.350 align:middle line:84%
are in these directions and
pass through at least one

00:24:41.350 --> 00:24:42.820 align:middle line:90%
of these points.

00:24:42.820 --> 00:24:46.870 align:middle line:84%
So that's a very particular
way of choosing the lines.

00:24:46.870 --> 00:24:50.290 align:middle line:84%
And there are not as
many sharp examples.

00:24:50.290 --> 00:24:54.310 align:middle line:84%
So taking one of
these grids and then

00:24:54.310 --> 00:24:57.880 align:middle line:84%
taking a set of
directions that are

00:24:57.880 --> 00:25:00.920 align:middle line:84%
rational numbers with small
numerators and denominators,

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:05.200 align:middle line:90%
that's a sharp example for this.

00:25:05.200 --> 00:25:08.440 align:middle line:84%
I think if you apply
point-line duality,

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:11.780 align:middle line:84%
that it's still a sharp
example for Szemerédi-Trotter,

00:25:11.780 --> 00:25:16.630 align:middle line:84%
but I don't think it is a
projection example anymore.

00:25:16.630 --> 00:25:18.730 align:middle line:90%
So let's see.

00:25:18.730 --> 00:25:27.340 align:middle line:84%
So being a projection example
means that for every point,

00:25:27.340 --> 00:25:32.530 align:middle line:84%
all of the lines going through
it have the same set of slopes.

00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:35.560 align:middle line:84%
Those are the directions
we're projecting.

00:25:35.560 --> 00:25:39.670 align:middle line:84%
So if I applied
point-line duality, that

00:25:39.670 --> 00:25:49.120 align:middle line:84%
would mean that for
every line, the set

00:25:49.120 --> 00:25:52.450 align:middle line:84%
of x-coordinates where
it intersects a point

00:25:52.450 --> 00:25:53.660 align:middle line:90%
would be the same.

00:25:53.660 --> 00:25:55.395 align:middle line:90%
And that's not true here.

00:25:55.395 --> 00:25:58.360 align:middle line:90%


00:25:58.360 --> 00:26:00.550 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's better you
may check on your own.

00:26:00.550 --> 00:26:03.370 align:middle line:84%
But so I claim if you
apply point-line duality,

00:26:03.370 --> 00:26:05.830 align:middle line:84%
you don't anymore have an
example with this projection

00:26:05.830 --> 00:26:07.240 align:middle line:90%
structure.

00:26:07.240 --> 00:26:09.970 align:middle line:84%
Also, if you apply a
projective transformation,

00:26:09.970 --> 00:26:14.470 align:middle line:84%
then you will ruin the fact that
there were parallel lines here.

00:26:14.470 --> 00:26:18.537 align:middle line:84%
So the directions, after
projective transformation,

00:26:18.537 --> 00:26:20.620 align:middle line:84%
the lines that used to
point in the same direction

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:22.370 align:middle line:84%
won't point in the
same direction anymore.

00:26:22.370 --> 00:26:24.910 align:middle line:84%
So that won't be a
projective example either.

00:26:24.910 --> 00:26:27.340 align:middle line:84%
So the class of
known sharp examples

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:29.830 align:middle line:84%
is smaller, which makes it a
little more hopeful that we

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:31.060 align:middle line:90%
could understand it.

00:26:31.060 --> 00:26:34.245 align:middle line:84%
It is actually just
grids over number fields.

00:26:34.245 --> 00:26:37.300 align:middle line:90%


00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:38.920 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:38.920 --> 00:26:44.260 align:middle line:84%
Now, once we set the
problem up this way,

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:50.560 align:middle line:84%
you could imagine fixing
the set D in advance,

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:52.730 align:middle line:84%
and then just for that
set of projections,

00:26:52.730 --> 00:26:55.173 align:middle line:84%
considering different sets
X and seeing what happens.

00:26:55.173 --> 00:26:57.340 align:middle line:84%
And so you get, actually,
lots of different problems

00:26:57.340 --> 00:26:59.475 align:middle line:84%
depending on what set
of directions you fix.

00:26:59.475 --> 00:27:02.200 align:middle line:90%


00:27:02.200 --> 00:27:03.510 align:middle line:90%
So let's write that down.

00:27:03.510 --> 00:27:17.560 align:middle line:90%


00:27:17.560 --> 00:27:18.760 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:27:18.760 --> 00:27:25.000 align:middle line:84%
So for any set D,
S sub D of N would

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:33.730 align:middle line:84%
be the minimum over any
set of N points of SXD,

00:27:33.730 --> 00:27:35.450 align:middle line:90%
which, remember what that is.

00:27:35.450 --> 00:27:38.410 align:middle line:84%
So it's the minimum
over any set of points

00:27:38.410 --> 00:27:43.540 align:middle line:84%
of the maximum over these
different projections of pi

00:27:43.540 --> 00:27:44.355 align:middle line:90%
theta of x.

00:27:44.355 --> 00:27:51.400 align:middle line:90%


00:27:51.400 --> 00:27:52.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:52.340 --> 00:27:57.370 align:middle line:90%
So, yeah.

00:27:57.370 --> 00:28:01.300 align:middle line:84%
So in my opinion, for any
set D that you write down,

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:03.410 align:middle line:84%
it's interesting to
try to estimate this.

00:28:03.410 --> 00:28:05.480 align:middle line:84%
So now we have lots
and lots of questions.

00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:07.030 align:middle line:84%
And most of those
questions have not

00:28:07.030 --> 00:28:11.440 align:middle line:90%
been investigated all that much.

00:28:11.440 --> 00:28:12.264 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:12.264 --> 00:28:15.050 align:middle line:84%
Now, in the sharp examples
that we know about,

00:28:15.050 --> 00:28:24.560 align:middle line:84%
who is D. In the
known sharp examples,

00:28:24.560 --> 00:28:29.090 align:middle line:84%
the set D is rational
numbers with small numerators

00:28:29.090 --> 00:28:48.110 align:middle line:84%
and denominators, or rational
fractions in some other ring.

00:28:48.110 --> 00:28:51.295 align:middle line:84%
So this is a ring of
integers in a number field.

00:28:51.295 --> 00:28:54.680 align:middle line:90%


00:28:54.680 --> 00:28:58.135 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll say this just more
informally, a and b are small.

00:28:58.135 --> 00:29:01.160 align:middle line:90%


00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:03.650 align:middle line:84%
So maybe the number fields
are things of the form a1

00:29:03.650 --> 00:29:10.160 align:middle line:84%
plus square root of 2, a2, and
a1 and a2 are small integers.

00:29:10.160 --> 00:29:13.610 align:middle line:84%
So in all the known
sharp examples,

00:29:13.610 --> 00:29:16.250 align:middle line:84%
these are the sets
of directions,

00:29:16.250 --> 00:29:19.310 align:middle line:84%
and they have quite a lot
of algebraic structure.

00:29:19.310 --> 00:29:21.620 align:middle line:84%
And so we could
ask the question,

00:29:21.620 --> 00:29:24.320 align:middle line:84%
if we fix a set of
directions that does not

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:26.730 align:middle line:84%
have so much
algebraic structure,

00:29:26.730 --> 00:29:29.910 align:middle line:84%
then can we get a
better estimate?

00:29:29.910 --> 00:29:32.420 align:middle line:90%


00:29:32.420 --> 00:29:35.058 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:29:35.058 --> 00:29:35.558 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:35.558 --> 00:29:38.366 align:middle line:90%


00:29:38.366 --> 00:29:40.370 align:middle line:90%
So let's think about--

00:29:40.370 --> 00:29:43.880 align:middle line:84%
we begin with the simplest
problem that we can.

00:29:43.880 --> 00:29:45.680 align:middle line:84%
So let's take just
a few directions--

00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:49.520 align:middle line:84%
two directions, three
directions, four directions.

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:50.340 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:29:50.340 --> 00:29:56.240 align:middle line:84%
So RMK, there is some linear
transformation symmetry

00:29:56.240 --> 00:29:56.980 align:middle line:90%
in this problem.

00:29:56.980 --> 00:30:02.020 align:middle line:90%


00:30:02.020 --> 00:30:02.520 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:04.670 align:middle line:84%
So if I start with the
configuration of points

00:30:04.670 --> 00:30:07.940 align:middle line:84%
and some directions, I can apply
a linear change of variables

00:30:07.940 --> 00:30:08.937 align:middle line:90%
to R2.

00:30:08.937 --> 00:30:10.520 align:middle line:84%
I'll get a new
configuration of points

00:30:10.520 --> 00:30:12.060 align:middle line:84%
and I'll get some
new directions,

00:30:12.060 --> 00:30:16.010 align:middle line:84%
but it'll be the same problem,
just in new coordinates.

00:30:16.010 --> 00:30:25.160 align:middle line:84%
So up to symmetry, if you
take just three directions,

00:30:25.160 --> 00:30:29.370 align:middle line:84%
then there's only one
choice up to symmetry.

00:30:29.370 --> 00:30:32.120 align:middle line:90%
So the set of directions--

00:30:32.120 --> 00:30:34.290 align:middle line:84%
ah, OK, actually, let
me say something else.

00:30:34.290 --> 00:30:34.880 align:middle line:90%
So OK.

00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:37.070 align:middle line:84%
So up to symmetry, if
there are three directions,

00:30:37.070 --> 00:30:38.530 align:middle line:90%
then there's only one choice.

00:30:38.530 --> 00:30:42.500 align:middle line:90%


00:30:42.500 --> 00:30:43.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:46.110 align:middle line:84%
Let me make a comment about how
to write down the directions.

00:30:46.110 --> 00:30:50.790 align:middle line:84%
I actually already was using it
without explaining it properly.

00:30:50.790 --> 00:30:55.850 align:middle line:84%
So this is the list of
slopes of the directions.

00:30:55.850 --> 00:30:57.410 align:middle line:90%
So OK.

00:30:57.410 --> 00:31:07.640 align:middle line:84%
So let's describe
our projections

00:31:07.640 --> 00:31:16.400 align:middle line:84%
as pi t key of X1 and X2
is X1 plus t times X2.

00:31:16.400 --> 00:31:19.640 align:middle line:84%
So for this investigation,
this t is more or less

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:22.700 align:middle line:84%
the slope of the projection, and
that is a more convenient thing

00:31:22.700 --> 00:31:26.390 align:middle line:84%
to talk about than
the angle in radians.

00:31:26.390 --> 00:31:29.540 align:middle line:84%
And that was what we
were writing up here.

00:31:29.540 --> 00:31:30.896 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:30.896 --> 00:31:34.520 align:middle line:90%
So, cool.

00:31:34.520 --> 00:31:40.280 align:middle line:84%
So for example, pi 0 of
x1x2 would just be x1.

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:42.050 align:middle line:84%
And the other
simplest projection

00:31:42.050 --> 00:31:43.740 align:middle line:90%
would be just to take x2.

00:31:43.740 --> 00:31:46.110 align:middle line:84%
And that doesn't quite
fit into this notation.

00:31:46.110 --> 00:31:50.010 align:middle line:84%
But there's a convention that
we'll call that pi infinity.

00:31:50.010 --> 00:31:54.290 align:middle line:90%
Pi infinity of x1x2 is just x2.

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:59.390 align:middle line:84%
And then all the other ones
will be t will be a real number.

00:31:59.390 --> 00:32:01.850 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:01.850 --> 00:32:07.760 align:middle line:84%
So if D equals 3, then
without loss of generality,

00:32:07.760 --> 00:32:11.370 align:middle line:90%
D might be 0, 1, and infinity.

00:32:11.370 --> 00:32:17.727 align:middle line:90%


00:32:17.727 --> 00:32:18.227 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:18.227 --> 00:32:43.755 align:middle line:90%


00:32:43.755 --> 00:32:44.255 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:44.255 --> 00:32:46.840 align:middle line:90%


00:32:46.840 --> 00:32:47.340 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:50.090 align:middle line:84%
So let me copy down what the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem says

00:32:50.090 --> 00:32:51.180 align:middle line:90%
for comparison.

00:32:51.180 --> 00:32:58.940 align:middle line:84%
It says for any set D, S of D
of N is at least D to the 1/2 N

00:32:58.940 --> 00:33:06.500 align:middle line:84%
to the 1/2 as long as there
are at least two points in D.

00:33:06.500 --> 00:33:13.040 align:middle line:84%
So if D is 0, 1, infinity,
or any set of three slopes,

00:33:13.040 --> 00:33:17.450 align:middle line:84%
because it's all the
same, this is sharp.

00:33:17.450 --> 00:33:20.450 align:middle line:84%
For instance, you could
take an N by N integer grid,

00:33:20.450 --> 00:33:23.430 align:middle line:84%
or N to the 1/2 by N to
the 1/2 integer grid.

00:33:23.430 --> 00:33:28.805 align:middle line:90%


00:33:28.805 --> 00:33:31.260 align:middle line:84%
So there's nothing new
for three directions.

00:33:31.260 --> 00:33:32.876 align:middle line:90%
Let's go to four directions.

00:33:32.876 --> 00:33:39.530 align:middle line:90%


00:33:39.530 --> 00:33:42.470 align:middle line:84%
By using our symmetry, we can
arrange that the first three

00:33:42.470 --> 00:33:45.170 align:middle line:84%
directions are 0,
1, and infinity,

00:33:45.170 --> 00:33:47.450 align:middle line:84%
and there'll be a
fourth direction, t.

00:33:47.450 --> 00:33:49.035 align:middle line:90%
And t could be any real number.

00:33:49.035 --> 00:33:50.660 align:middle line:84%
So we have one degree
of freedom how we

00:33:50.660 --> 00:33:53.300 align:middle line:90%
would choose four directions.

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:55.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:55.690 --> 00:34:00.240 align:middle line:84%
And the one extreme, we could
choose t to be like 1/2 or 2.

00:34:00.240 --> 00:34:04.950 align:middle line:84%
And so this would be
rational with a small size.

00:34:04.950 --> 00:34:06.870 align:middle line:84%
And then the other
extreme, we could

00:34:06.870 --> 00:34:10.620 align:middle line:84%
say that t might be a
transcendental number.

00:34:10.620 --> 00:34:12.880 align:middle line:84%
And somewhere in the middle
we would have root 2,

00:34:12.880 --> 00:34:17.550 align:middle line:84%
or a big rational number, like
1,000 or something like that.

00:34:17.550 --> 00:34:23.105 align:middle line:84%
Now in this case,
the theorem is sharp.

00:34:23.105 --> 00:34:28.739 align:middle line:90%


00:34:28.739 --> 00:34:31.500 align:middle line:84%
So the example that we have
with four directions, the four

00:34:31.500 --> 00:34:34.380 align:middle line:90%
directions would be these.

00:34:34.380 --> 00:34:38.699 align:middle line:84%
And in this case, it's a
question what would happen.

00:34:38.699 --> 00:34:41.310 align:middle line:84%
So let me write a
specific question.

00:34:41.310 --> 00:34:42.364 align:middle line:90%
So question.

00:34:42.364 --> 00:34:46.139 align:middle line:90%


00:34:46.139 --> 00:34:58.470 align:middle line:84%
So if D is 0, 1, infinity, and
t, where t is transcendental,

00:34:58.470 --> 00:35:06.990 align:middle line:84%
then is it true that SD of N
is bounded by N to the 1/2?

00:35:06.990 --> 00:35:09.600 align:middle line:90%


00:35:09.600 --> 00:35:11.590 align:middle line:90%
So it's at least N to the 1/2.

00:35:11.590 --> 00:35:14.430 align:middle line:84%
If the theorem is sharp,
it would be approximately N

00:35:14.430 --> 00:35:15.220 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:35:15.220 --> 00:35:17.680 align:middle line:84%
But if the theorem is not
sharp and we can improve it,

00:35:17.680 --> 00:35:19.730 align:middle line:90%
it might be bigger than this.

00:35:19.730 --> 00:35:25.830 align:middle line:90%


00:35:25.830 --> 00:35:28.810 align:middle line:84%
My best guess is that
it's bigger than this.

00:35:28.810 --> 00:35:31.030 align:middle line:84%
And I played around a
little bit with examples.

00:35:31.030 --> 00:35:34.580 align:middle line:84%
And I can show you the best
example that I can find.

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:37.990 align:middle line:90%


00:35:37.990 --> 00:35:38.490 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:38.490 --> 00:35:59.730 align:middle line:90%


00:35:59.730 --> 00:36:00.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:01.213 align:middle line:90%
So example.

00:36:01.213 --> 00:36:04.260 align:middle line:90%


00:36:04.260 --> 00:36:09.840 align:middle line:84%
Let me say that PKS is
the set of polynomials

00:36:09.840 --> 00:36:11.790 align:middle line:90%
in this transcendental number t.

00:36:11.790 --> 00:36:19.810 align:middle line:84%
So a0 plus a1t plus aK
minus 1 t to the K minus 1.

00:36:19.810 --> 00:36:22.920 align:middle line:84%
So they are degree
K polynomials.

00:36:22.920 --> 00:36:28.510 align:middle line:84%
And the a's are integers,
and they have size up to S.

00:36:28.510 --> 00:36:30.605 align:middle line:90%
So let's say this.

00:36:30.605 --> 00:36:37.950 align:middle line:90%


00:36:37.950 --> 00:36:42.360 align:middle line:84%
So that guy is going to play
the role like integers from 1

00:36:42.360 --> 00:36:46.710 align:middle line:84%
up to S, and that
would have worked well

00:36:46.710 --> 00:36:50.160 align:middle line:90%
if we had a rational slope.

00:36:50.160 --> 00:36:56.490 align:middle line:84%
So now our set S is going
to be PKS times PKS.

00:36:56.490 --> 00:36:58.090 align:middle line:84%
K and S, of course,
are parameters.

00:36:58.090 --> 00:37:01.950 align:middle line:84%
So we can play with them
and see what's optimal.

00:37:01.950 --> 00:37:06.870 align:middle line:90%
So the size of X is S to the 2K.

00:37:06.870 --> 00:37:08.920 align:middle line:84%
Besides, if this
thing is S to the K,

00:37:08.920 --> 00:37:14.580 align:middle line:84%
we have K choices and S
choices for each of ai.

00:37:14.580 --> 00:37:15.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:18.840 align:middle line:84%
Now what happens
when we project X?

00:37:18.840 --> 00:37:23.940 align:middle line:84%
Pi 0 of X projection onto the
first coordinate is just PKS,

00:37:23.940 --> 00:37:27.450 align:middle line:84%
and pi infinity
of X is projection

00:37:27.450 --> 00:37:28.720 align:middle line:90%
onto the second coordinate.

00:37:28.720 --> 00:37:31.200 align:middle line:90%
That's just PKS.

00:37:31.200 --> 00:37:33.040 align:middle line:90%
Those are quite small.

00:37:33.040 --> 00:37:35.700 align:middle line:90%
Best we could hope for, really.

00:37:35.700 --> 00:37:40.620 align:middle line:90%
Now, what is pi 1 of X?

00:37:40.620 --> 00:37:44.880 align:middle line:84%
Pi 1 of X is I take
an element of here

00:37:44.880 --> 00:37:47.610 align:middle line:84%
and I add it to an
element of here.

00:37:47.610 --> 00:37:50.130 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to add
this set to itself.

00:37:50.130 --> 00:37:51.690 align:middle line:84%
When I take two of
these polynomials

00:37:51.690 --> 00:37:54.120 align:middle line:84%
and add them together,
I get a new polynomial,

00:37:54.120 --> 00:37:56.020 align:middle line:90%
and I just add the coefficients.

00:37:56.020 --> 00:38:02.410 align:middle line:84%
So the the constant coefficient
was between 0 and S minus 1,

00:38:02.410 --> 00:38:04.180 align:middle line:90%
and I add up two of those.

00:38:04.180 --> 00:38:07.500 align:middle line:84%
The sum is between
0 and 2S, basically.

00:38:07.500 --> 00:38:12.690 align:middle line:84%
So pi 1 of X is
contained in PK comma 2S.

00:38:12.690 --> 00:38:15.780 align:middle line:90%


00:38:15.780 --> 00:38:19.980 align:middle line:84%
And it's pretty
much equal to that.

00:38:19.980 --> 00:38:20.585 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:38:20.585 --> 00:38:23.220 align:middle line:90%


00:38:23.220 --> 00:38:28.530 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happens
if I take pi t of X?

00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:32.620 align:middle line:84%
Well, pi t of X means I'm going
to take X1, which is in here,

00:38:32.620 --> 00:38:35.950 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to add
it to t times X2.

00:38:35.950 --> 00:38:36.970 align:middle line:90%
X2 lives in here.

00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:41.412 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to multiply it
by t and add it to X1.

00:38:41.412 --> 00:38:42.360 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:38:42.360 --> 00:38:45.940 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
most important one.

00:38:45.940 --> 00:38:50.100 align:middle line:84%
And these were designed to
make this reasonably small.

00:38:50.100 --> 00:38:52.110 align:middle line:90%
So what's going to happen?

00:38:52.110 --> 00:38:57.040 align:middle line:84%
Well, t times X2 is going to
be a polynomial like this,

00:38:57.040 --> 00:39:01.330 align:middle line:84%
but it will have degree
K instead of K minus 1.

00:39:01.330 --> 00:39:05.890 align:middle line:84%
And then I will add it to X1,
which is a polynomial like this.

00:39:05.890 --> 00:39:09.610 align:middle line:84%
When I put them together, I'll
get a polynomial of degree K,

00:39:09.610 --> 00:39:12.760 align:middle line:84%
and the coefficients
will be up to 2S.

00:39:12.760 --> 00:39:19.930 align:middle line:84%
So this is contained
in PK plus 1 2S.

00:39:19.930 --> 00:39:24.340 align:middle line:84%
And this one is the largest
of the four projections.

00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:25.570 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:39:25.570 --> 00:39:27.820 align:middle line:84%
It's a bit smaller
than this, but I doubt

00:39:27.820 --> 00:39:29.680 align:middle line:90%
that it matters very much.

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:33.940 align:middle line:84%
So let's just think of it
as being about this big.

00:39:33.940 --> 00:39:35.380 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:39:35.380 --> 00:39:38.630 align:middle line:84%
So S is the size of
the biggest projection.

00:39:38.630 --> 00:39:40.930 align:middle line:84%
This one is the
biggest projection.

00:39:40.930 --> 00:39:48.270 align:middle line:84%
And that is roughly
2S to the K plus 1.

00:39:48.270 --> 00:39:52.480 align:middle line:90%


00:39:52.480 --> 00:39:53.390 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:39:53.390 --> 00:39:55.990 align:middle line:84%
So let me digest
it a little bit.

00:39:55.990 --> 00:39:59.350 align:middle line:90%
It's 2 to the K plus 1.

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:01.750 align:middle line:84%
The plus 1 doesn't
matter very much.

00:40:01.750 --> 00:40:09.100 align:middle line:84%
And then S, and then
S to the K. S to the K

00:40:09.100 --> 00:40:12.560 align:middle line:84%
is the square root of X.
That's what we're shooting for.

00:40:12.560 --> 00:40:16.030 align:middle line:84%
We're trying to get as close as
we can to the square root of X.

00:40:16.030 --> 00:40:20.540 align:middle line:90%
So 2 to the K is X to the 1/2.

00:40:20.540 --> 00:40:22.610 align:middle line:90%
And then there's an S here.

00:40:22.610 --> 00:40:26.590 align:middle line:84%
And the S is the size
of X to the 1 over 2K.

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:35.020 align:middle line:90%


00:40:35.020 --> 00:40:35.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:35.840 --> 00:40:38.510 align:middle line:84%
So I want to try to get
as close to this as I can.

00:40:38.510 --> 00:40:40.640 align:middle line:84%
So I want to
minimize this thing.

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:44.770 align:middle line:84%
So now we're going to
choose K to minimize it.

00:40:44.770 --> 00:40:47.722 align:middle line:90%


00:40:47.722 --> 00:40:50.595 align:middle line:84%
K should also be an integer,
but that's not a big issue.

00:40:50.595 --> 00:40:55.150 align:middle line:90%


00:40:55.150 --> 00:40:56.590 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:40:56.590 --> 00:40:57.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:57.470 --> 00:41:00.740 align:middle line:84%
Well, if I want to minimize
this product, at least roughly,

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:04.420 align:middle line:84%
the thing to do is to make
this one equal to this one.

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:11.780 align:middle line:84%
So let's set 2 to the K to be
equal to X to the 1 over 2K.

00:41:11.780 --> 00:41:13.700 align:middle line:90%
And now we'll solve for K.

00:41:13.700 --> 00:41:16.700 align:middle line:84%
First, I raise both
sides to the 2K power.

00:41:16.700 --> 00:41:21.490 align:middle line:84%
So I get 2 to the
2K squared is X.

00:41:21.490 --> 00:41:24.260 align:middle line:84%
Now I'll take the
logarithm of both sides.

00:41:24.260 --> 00:41:30.610 align:middle line:84%
So 2K squared is the
logarithm base 2 of X.

00:41:30.610 --> 00:41:32.200 align:middle line:84%
And now I'll solve
for K. And there's

00:41:32.200 --> 00:41:35.450 align:middle line:84%
some constants that let's
not worry about too much.

00:41:35.450 --> 00:41:41.180 align:middle line:84%
So K is equal to some constant
times the log of X to the 1/2.

00:41:41.180 --> 00:41:48.310 align:middle line:90%


00:41:48.310 --> 00:41:51.250 align:middle line:90%
So now how big was this thing?

00:41:51.250 --> 00:41:55.100 align:middle line:84%
It's either one of these
things are equal to each other,

00:41:55.100 --> 00:41:57.440 align:middle line:84%
and this one is maybe
easier to understand.

00:41:57.440 --> 00:41:59.130 align:middle line:90%
It's 2 to that.

00:41:59.130 --> 00:42:02.020 align:middle line:90%


00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:13.930 align:middle line:84%
So our S sub D of this set X is
like e to a constant log of X

00:42:13.930 --> 00:42:17.150 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2 X to the 1/2.

00:42:17.150 --> 00:42:22.880 align:middle line:90%


00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:23.380 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:42:23.380 --> 00:42:26.650 align:middle line:90%


00:42:26.650 --> 00:42:27.320 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:42:27.320 --> 00:42:30.860 align:middle line:84%
So asymptotically, as the
size of X goes to infinity,

00:42:30.860 --> 00:42:35.440 align:middle line:84%
this thing is smaller
than X to the 0.51.

00:42:35.440 --> 00:42:39.610 align:middle line:84%
But it's also, this thing
is bigger than any constant.

00:42:39.610 --> 00:42:40.670 align:middle line:90%
It is going to infinity.

00:42:40.670 --> 00:42:44.760 align:middle line:84%
So it's also not less
than x to the 1/2.

00:42:44.760 --> 00:42:48.550 align:middle line:90%


00:42:48.550 --> 00:42:49.230 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:49.230 --> 00:42:54.910 align:middle line:84%
So this was just one
example, S sub D of N.

00:42:54.910 --> 00:43:03.250 align:middle line:84%
So this tells us that S sub D of
N is less than e to a constant

00:43:03.250 --> 00:43:08.320 align:middle line:84%
log of N to the
1/2 N to the 1/2.

00:43:08.320 --> 00:43:10.690 align:middle line:84%
And this by definition
is the minimum

00:43:10.690 --> 00:43:13.250 align:middle line:84%
over all the possible
sets X of size N.

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:15.490 align:middle line:90%
And this was just one of them.

00:43:15.490 --> 00:43:20.110 align:middle line:84%
But I think it's plausible that
this is the one with smallest

00:43:20.110 --> 00:43:22.720 align:middle line:90%
projections.

00:43:22.720 --> 00:43:24.193 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:24.193 --> 00:43:28.750 align:middle line:84%
So plausibly, that
gives a sense of how

00:43:28.750 --> 00:43:31.030 align:middle line:84%
things, for four
directions, how do

00:43:31.030 --> 00:43:36.790 align:middle line:84%
things change when you go from a
transcendental thing on the one

00:43:36.790 --> 00:43:41.295 align:middle line:84%
side to a very nice rational
slope on the other side.

00:43:41.295 --> 00:43:48.310 align:middle line:90%


00:43:48.310 --> 00:43:49.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:49.070 --> 00:43:49.640 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:43:49.640 --> 00:43:52.980 align:middle line:84%
And that, I mean, that's of the
beginning of an investigation.

00:43:52.980 --> 00:43:57.080 align:middle line:84%
Of course, we could
have more directions.

00:43:57.080 --> 00:43:59.636 align:middle line:90%
And so we have many questions.

00:43:59.636 --> 00:44:13.220 align:middle line:90%


00:44:13.220 --> 00:44:15.710 align:middle line:84%
So four directions is
already complicated enough

00:44:15.710 --> 00:44:16.970 align:middle line:90%
to be interesting.

00:44:16.970 --> 00:44:20.160 align:middle line:84%
But wow, we could also
have many directions.

00:44:20.160 --> 00:44:22.230 align:middle line:84%
And so we would have
lots more questions.

00:44:22.230 --> 00:44:28.730 align:middle line:90%


00:44:28.730 --> 00:44:32.360 align:middle line:90%
So more questions.

00:44:32.360 --> 00:44:36.800 align:middle line:84%
So maybe D is 0, 1, and
infinity, and then a bunch

00:44:36.800 --> 00:44:39.530 align:middle line:90%
more directions.

00:44:39.530 --> 00:44:41.660 align:middle line:90%
So we have R directions.

00:44:41.660 --> 00:44:48.240 align:middle line:84%
And the sharp
example, these guys

00:44:48.240 --> 00:44:51.240 align:middle line:84%
were rational numbers, or
rational numbers in some field

00:44:51.240 --> 00:44:53.160 align:middle line:90%
with small heights.

00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:58.800 align:middle line:84%
The opposite of that
would be maybe t1 up to tR

00:44:58.800 --> 00:45:03.750 align:middle line:84%
are algebraically
independent over Q.

00:45:03.750 --> 00:45:05.140 align:middle line:90%
So they're each transcendental.

00:45:05.140 --> 00:45:07.390 align:middle line:84%
But even more than that,
there's no algebraic relation

00:45:07.390 --> 00:45:08.200 align:middle line:90%
among all of them.

00:45:08.200 --> 00:45:12.120 align:middle line:84%
This would be the most
transcendental situation.

00:45:12.120 --> 00:45:15.455 align:middle line:90%
So then how does this behave?

00:45:15.455 --> 00:45:27.118 align:middle line:90%


00:45:27.118 --> 00:45:28.660 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
stuff in the middle.

00:45:28.660 --> 00:45:32.350 align:middle line:84%
So maybe these guys could live
in a field extension of Q,

00:45:32.350 --> 00:45:34.300 align:middle line:90%
which is pretty complicated.

00:45:34.300 --> 00:45:36.360 align:middle line:84%
And so potentially, there
could be an interaction

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:39.210 align:middle line:84%
between algebraic
number theory, where

00:45:39.210 --> 00:45:41.070 align:middle line:84%
it's a discipline
that describes who

00:45:41.070 --> 00:45:43.230 align:middle line:84%
are the field
extensions of Q. How

00:45:43.230 --> 00:45:46.330 align:middle line:84%
do you think about them
with projection theory?

00:45:46.330 --> 00:45:49.908 align:middle line:90%


00:45:49.908 --> 00:45:52.200 align:middle line:84%
So people coming into class
have different backgrounds.

00:45:52.200 --> 00:45:53.617 align:middle line:84%
I'm not sure if
there's anyone who

00:45:53.617 --> 00:45:57.080 align:middle line:84%
does number theory and
algebraic number theory.

00:45:57.080 --> 00:46:01.492 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, so this
is a possible project.

00:46:01.492 --> 00:46:03.200 align:middle line:84%
In the weeks ahead,
we'll be talking more

00:46:03.200 --> 00:46:05.880 align:middle line:84%
about different
types of projects.

00:46:05.880 --> 00:46:07.520 align:middle line:84%
And everybody can
pick out something

00:46:07.520 --> 00:46:09.710 align:middle line:84%
that they want to work on
for their final project

00:46:09.710 --> 00:46:10.315 align:middle line:90%
for the class.

00:46:10.315 --> 00:46:17.660 align:middle line:90%


00:46:17.660 --> 00:46:18.280 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:46:18.280 --> 00:46:18.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:18.780 --> 00:46:22.340 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or
comments about this?

00:46:22.340 --> 00:46:28.130 align:middle line:84%
This is my stab at having some
warm-up questions that lead

00:46:28.130 --> 00:46:30.875 align:middle line:84%
towards thinking about the
structure of sharp examples

00:46:30.875 --> 00:46:32.125 align:middle line:90%
for Szemerédi-Trotter Trotter.

00:46:32.125 --> 00:46:39.200 align:middle line:90%


00:46:39.200 --> 00:46:40.700 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Or what
you're saying, you

00:46:40.700 --> 00:46:43.130 align:middle line:84%
expect that you can prove
something stronger for this case

00:46:43.130 --> 00:46:45.150 align:middle line:84%
where everything is
algebraically independent?

00:46:45.150 --> 00:46:47.557 align:middle line:90%


00:46:47.557 --> 00:46:48.390 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:46:48.390 --> 00:46:49.650 align:middle line:90%
If I had to guess--

00:46:49.650 --> 00:46:52.820 align:middle line:84%
so I think the question is,
what do I guess is true?

00:46:52.820 --> 00:46:57.590 align:middle line:84%
If I had to guess, I would
guess that there are-- sorry,

00:46:57.590 --> 00:47:01.520 align:middle line:84%
this should be S sub D of N.
There are much stronger lower

00:47:01.520 --> 00:47:05.223 align:middle line:84%
bounds for this than the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem

00:47:05.223 --> 00:47:06.390 align:middle line:90%
if these are all transitive.

00:47:06.390 --> 00:47:09.150 align:middle line:84%
This is if there are no
algebraic relations there.

00:47:09.150 --> 00:47:22.340 align:middle line:90%


00:47:22.340 --> 00:47:22.860 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:47:22.860 --> 00:47:25.070 align:middle line:84%
So for this setup,
you could make

00:47:25.070 --> 00:47:27.960 align:middle line:84%
a class of examples that
is kind of like this class.

00:47:27.960 --> 00:47:30.900 align:middle line:84%
But instead of having
polynomials in just one thing t,

00:47:30.900 --> 00:47:34.700 align:middle line:84%
there would be polynomials
in t1 up to tR.

00:47:34.700 --> 00:47:36.950 align:middle line:84%
And I don't know if you
could count the total degree,

00:47:36.950 --> 00:47:38.010 align:middle line:90%
or I'm not sure.

00:47:38.010 --> 00:47:38.663 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:47:38.663 --> 00:47:40.830 align:middle line:84%
So there's some example you
could get your hands on.

00:47:40.830 --> 00:47:43.110 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's plausible
that that's the sharp example.

00:47:43.110 --> 00:47:45.443 align:middle line:84%
And that I think it's plausible
that the bounds are much

00:47:45.443 --> 00:47:47.690 align:middle line:84%
stronger than the general
Szemerédi-Trotter bound.

00:47:47.690 --> 00:47:49.530 align:middle line:84%
And I would be really
interested to--

00:47:49.530 --> 00:47:51.530 align:middle line:84%
or I could be wrong, also,
but I would be really

00:47:51.530 --> 00:47:52.870 align:middle line:90%
interested in either case.

00:47:52.870 --> 00:48:00.020 align:middle line:90%


00:48:00.020 --> 00:48:00.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:00.870 --> 00:48:06.110 align:middle line:84%
So let's circle back
to our class outline.

00:48:06.110 --> 00:48:09.710 align:middle line:84%
So the Szemerédi-Trotter proof
doesn't tell us much about

00:48:09.710 --> 00:48:11.610 align:middle line:84%
projection theory
for finite fields.

00:48:11.610 --> 00:48:13.620 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk more about
that next class.

00:48:13.620 --> 00:48:16.520 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't tell us much about
the structure of sharp examples

00:48:16.520 --> 00:48:18.900 align:middle line:84%
for the Szemerédi-Trotter
theorem over the reals.

00:48:18.900 --> 00:48:20.160 align:middle line:90%
We just talked about that.

00:48:20.160 --> 00:48:23.630 align:middle line:84%
And it doesn't tell us very much
about projection theory for unit

00:48:23.630 --> 00:48:24.390 align:middle line:90%
balls.

00:48:24.390 --> 00:48:26.160 align:middle line:90%
So let's talk about this one.

00:48:26.160 --> 00:48:28.740 align:middle line:84%
This is perhaps the
central topic in our class.

00:48:28.740 --> 00:48:30.540 align:middle line:84%
And let's see what
the problem is,

00:48:30.540 --> 00:48:35.840 align:middle line:84%
why this complete, elegant
solution of the projection

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:39.050 align:middle line:84%
problem for points in R2
doesn't tell us very much

00:48:39.050 --> 00:48:41.640 align:middle line:84%
about the projection problem
for unit balls in R2.

00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:53.530 align:middle line:90%


00:48:53.530 --> 00:48:54.030 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:48:54.030 --> 00:48:58.100 align:middle line:84%
So first, let's recall
what is the projection

00:48:58.100 --> 00:49:00.760 align:middle line:84%
problem for unit balls, and
what is Hausdorff spacing.

00:49:00.760 --> 00:49:13.700 align:middle line:90%


00:49:13.700 --> 00:49:15.350 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:49:15.350 --> 00:49:18.020 align:middle line:90%
So let's set up.

00:49:18.020 --> 00:49:19.020 align:middle line:90%
All right, let me write.

00:49:19.020 --> 00:49:28.910 align:middle line:90%


00:49:28.910 --> 00:49:29.490 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:49:29.490 --> 00:49:40.230 align:middle line:84%
So X is now a set of unit balls
In the ball of radius R in R2.

00:49:40.230 --> 00:49:42.100 align:middle line:90%
And D is a set of directions.

00:49:42.100 --> 00:49:45.630 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to think of it
as a subset of the circle.

00:49:45.630 --> 00:49:48.780 align:middle line:84%
And their directions
are 1 over R separated,

00:49:48.780 --> 00:49:51.600 align:middle line:84%
because otherwise they would
be equivalent from the point

00:49:51.600 --> 00:49:55.170 align:middle line:84%
of view of projecting
some unit balls in BR.

00:49:55.170 --> 00:49:56.070 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:49:56.070 --> 00:49:59.006 align:middle line:84%
S of XD is the
largest projection.

00:49:59.006 --> 00:50:04.760 align:middle line:90%


00:50:04.760 --> 00:50:05.260 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:50:05.260 --> 00:50:08.740 align:middle line:84%
And this symbol is
now doing double duty,

00:50:08.740 --> 00:50:13.080 align:middle line:84%
and we're thinking of it as
the length of the projection.

00:50:13.080 --> 00:50:14.301 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:14.301 --> 00:50:20.130 align:middle line:84%
So we'd like to understand
how these things behave.

00:50:20.130 --> 00:50:23.190 align:middle line:84%
But besides looking at
the cardinality of X

00:50:23.190 --> 00:50:24.960 align:middle line:84%
and the cardinality
of D, we're also

00:50:24.960 --> 00:50:27.690 align:middle line:84%
going to pay attention
to their spacing.

00:50:27.690 --> 00:50:33.480 align:middle line:84%
So N sub X of r is
the maximum of X

00:50:33.480 --> 00:50:37.150 align:middle line:84%
intersected with a ball of
radius little r with any center.

00:50:37.150 --> 00:50:39.990 align:middle line:84%
So it's the maximum
over the center.

00:50:39.990 --> 00:50:44.850 align:middle line:84%
And N sub D over
rho is the maximum

00:50:44.850 --> 00:50:48.360 align:middle line:84%
of D intersect
gamma, where gamma

00:50:48.360 --> 00:50:51.750 align:middle line:84%
is an arc of length
rho in the circle.

00:50:51.750 --> 00:50:56.580 align:middle line:84%
So this describes how X and D
are packed at smaller scales,

00:50:56.580 --> 00:50:57.575 align:middle line:90%
or how they're spaced.

00:50:57.575 --> 00:51:02.010 align:middle line:90%


00:51:02.010 --> 00:51:08.370 align:middle line:84%
So Hausdorff
spacing means that X

00:51:08.370 --> 00:51:13.140 align:middle line:84%
is around R to the alpha for
some pre-parameter alpha,

00:51:13.140 --> 00:51:17.190 align:middle line:84%
and N sub X of little r
is bounded by little r

00:51:17.190 --> 00:51:19.890 align:middle line:90%
to the alpha.

00:51:19.890 --> 00:51:22.493 align:middle line:84%
That's Hausdorff spacing
for X. Hausdorff spacing

00:51:22.493 --> 00:51:24.660 align:middle line:84%
for the directions would
be the number of directions

00:51:24.660 --> 00:51:31.290 align:middle line:84%
is R to the beta, and ND
of little r over big R

00:51:31.290 --> 00:51:33.440 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by little
r to the beta.

00:51:33.440 --> 00:51:37.140 align:middle line:90%


00:51:37.140 --> 00:51:39.810 align:middle line:84%
So this informally says
that the balls of X

00:51:39.810 --> 00:51:42.400 align:middle line:84%
are not packed too much
into a smaller ball,

00:51:42.400 --> 00:51:44.430 align:middle line:84%
and the directions are
not packed too much

00:51:44.430 --> 00:51:47.366 align:middle line:84%
into a smaller direction, into
a small band of directions.

00:51:47.366 --> 00:51:49.920 align:middle line:90%


00:51:49.920 --> 00:51:55.830 align:middle line:84%
These exact conditions,
it's not the only conditions

00:51:55.830 --> 00:51:56.980 align:middle line:90%
one might be interested in.

00:51:56.980 --> 00:51:58.350 align:middle line:84%
It's not the only
spacing condition

00:51:58.350 --> 00:52:00.058 align:middle line:84%
that might be interesting
to think about,

00:52:00.058 --> 00:52:02.230 align:middle line:84%
but it's one of the
most popular ones.

00:52:02.230 --> 00:52:07.770 align:middle line:84%
And it has turned out that
the most interesting math

00:52:07.770 --> 00:52:12.360 align:middle line:84%
has come up by trying to
understand these conditions.

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:13.210 align:middle line:90%
And they come up.

00:52:13.210 --> 00:52:15.820 align:middle line:84%
They come up naturally
in some points of view,

00:52:15.820 --> 00:52:17.283 align:middle line:90%
even though they're also--

00:52:17.283 --> 00:52:19.200 align:middle line:84%
I will argue that other
spacing conditions are

00:52:19.200 --> 00:52:20.950 align:middle line:90%
helpful to consider sometimes.

00:52:20.950 --> 00:52:25.380 align:middle line:90%


00:52:25.380 --> 00:52:27.750 align:middle line:90%
So that's Hausdorff spacing.

00:52:27.750 --> 00:52:31.110 align:middle line:84%
And the analog of the
Szemerédi-Trotter problem is

00:52:31.110 --> 00:52:35.010 align:middle line:84%
going to be try to understand
this if X and D have Hausdorff

00:52:35.010 --> 00:52:36.150 align:middle line:90%
spacing.

00:52:36.150 --> 00:52:39.316 align:middle line:90%
So question.

00:52:39.316 --> 00:52:44.345 align:middle line:84%
If X and D have
Hausdorff spacing--

00:52:44.345 --> 00:52:48.510 align:middle line:90%


00:52:48.510 --> 00:52:54.240 align:middle line:84%
wow, let me put up a conjecture,
which is even now a theorem--

00:52:54.240 --> 00:53:00.080 align:middle line:84%
then D is less S
squared over X plus 1.

00:53:00.080 --> 00:53:04.230 align:middle line:90%


00:53:04.230 --> 00:53:06.330 align:middle line:84%
So this was an old
conjecture, and now it's

00:53:06.330 --> 00:53:10.470 align:middle line:84%
a theorem proven by Orponen
and Shmerkin and Ren and Wang.

00:53:10.470 --> 00:53:14.100 align:middle line:84%
And it's totally analogous to
the Szemerédi-Trotter projection

00:53:14.100 --> 00:53:15.910 align:middle line:90%
theorem for finite point sets.

00:53:15.910 --> 00:53:18.030 align:middle line:84%
But the proof of the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem

00:53:18.030 --> 00:53:21.480 align:middle line:84%
doesn't help very much
to prove this stuff.

00:53:21.480 --> 00:53:22.695 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:22.695 --> 00:53:23.840 align:middle line:90%
So what goes wrong?

00:53:23.840 --> 00:53:42.510 align:middle line:90%


00:53:42.510 --> 00:53:43.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:43.010 --> 00:53:48.416 align:middle line:90%


00:53:48.416 --> 00:53:52.445 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to use the
cell decomposition method.

00:53:52.445 --> 00:53:56.430 align:middle line:90%


00:53:56.430 --> 00:54:17.430 align:middle line:90%
So here's X.

00:54:17.430 --> 00:54:21.090 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me
back up a second.

00:54:21.090 --> 00:54:23.910 align:middle line:84%
So to see what goes wrong, it
helps to remember how the cell

00:54:23.910 --> 00:54:27.400 align:middle line:84%
decomposition method worked for
the original Szemerédi-Trotter,

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:28.780 align:middle line:90%
which we did go over.

00:54:28.780 --> 00:54:31.660 align:middle line:84%
But let me go over it in the
context of this projection

00:54:31.660 --> 00:54:32.300 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:54:32.300 --> 00:54:34.630 align:middle line:84%
And so you can see how it
looks there so that we'll

00:54:34.630 --> 00:54:35.535 align:middle line:90%
be able to compare.

00:54:35.535 --> 00:54:41.050 align:middle line:90%


00:54:41.050 --> 00:54:41.670 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:54:41.670 --> 00:54:48.310 align:middle line:90%


00:54:48.310 --> 00:54:51.287 align:middle line:84%
I do realize that this is maybe
the third time that we have

00:54:51.287 --> 00:54:53.620 align:middle line:84%
outlined the proof of the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem with

00:54:53.620 --> 00:54:57.340 align:middle line:84%
the cell decompositions,
but well,

00:54:57.340 --> 00:54:58.910 align:middle line:90%
really good pieces of math.

00:54:58.910 --> 00:55:02.530 align:middle line:90%
It's OK to see a few times.

00:55:02.530 --> 00:55:03.170 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:55:03.170 --> 00:55:12.160 align:middle line:84%
So sketch of ST proof,
ST projection proof

00:55:12.160 --> 00:55:19.840 align:middle line:90%
using cell decompositions.

00:55:19.840 --> 00:55:21.720 align:middle line:90%
So we have a set X of points.

00:55:21.720 --> 00:55:30.310 align:middle line:90%


00:55:30.310 --> 00:55:36.400 align:middle line:84%
So here's X. And then
I cut it into cells.

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:41.740 align:middle line:90%
And Xi is X intersect Oi.

00:55:41.740 --> 00:55:44.710 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to do my
cell decomposition.

00:55:44.710 --> 00:55:50.360 align:middle line:84%
And it has a parameter,
which I called S before,

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:51.970 align:middle line:84%
but I'm going to
call it sigma now

00:55:51.970 --> 00:55:56.980 align:middle line:84%
because we have this other
letter S, and it gets confusing.

00:55:56.980 --> 00:56:02.445 align:middle line:84%
So the size of Xi is like
X over sigma squared.

00:56:02.445 --> 00:56:06.130 align:middle line:90%


00:56:06.130 --> 00:56:06.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:06.630 --> 00:56:11.130 align:middle line:90%


00:56:11.130 --> 00:56:18.940 align:middle line:84%
Now, we're going to draw all
the-- so the set L, our lines,

00:56:18.940 --> 00:56:32.980 align:middle line:84%
are going to be all the lines
through x with a slope in D.

00:56:32.980 --> 00:56:36.290 align:middle line:84%
And when we just
look at this cell,

00:56:36.290 --> 00:56:38.740 align:middle line:84%
we're still doing
the projections

00:56:38.740 --> 00:56:40.130 align:middle line:90%
in all the same directions.

00:56:40.130 --> 00:56:46.340 align:middle line:90%
We have the same D.

00:56:46.340 --> 00:56:46.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:47.340 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:56:47.340 --> 00:56:49.000 align:middle line:90%
Let me write down our--

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:53.000 align:middle line:90%
So Di is the same as D. OK.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:56.646 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a double
counting observation.

00:56:56.646 --> 00:57:01.210 align:middle line:90%


00:57:01.210 --> 00:57:03.070 align:middle line:84%
And the double
counting observation

00:57:03.070 --> 00:57:05.620 align:middle line:84%
says that if the
number of directions

00:57:05.620 --> 00:57:07.960 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than the number
of points, maybe twice

00:57:07.960 --> 00:57:12.190 align:middle line:84%
the number of
points, then S should

00:57:12.190 --> 00:57:16.840 align:middle line:84%
be at least around
the number of points.

00:57:16.840 --> 00:57:19.900 align:middle line:84%
And the reason for that is
that if you have this many

00:57:19.900 --> 00:57:27.460 align:middle line:84%
directions, and the typical
point for most of the directions

00:57:27.460 --> 00:57:30.820 align:middle line:84%
you're projecting, it
cannot hit any other point.

00:57:30.820 --> 00:57:33.260 align:middle line:84%
So in most directions
when you project a point--

00:57:33.260 --> 00:57:35.030 align:middle line:90%
so we have this point.

00:57:35.030 --> 00:57:37.130 align:middle line:84%
We have a handful
of other points.

00:57:37.130 --> 00:57:42.100 align:middle line:84%
But then we're going to project
this point in many directions.

00:57:42.100 --> 00:57:43.380 align:middle line:90%
So there.

00:57:43.380 --> 00:57:51.100 align:middle line:90%


00:57:51.100 --> 00:57:53.380 align:middle line:84%
So let's say we
have more than twice

00:57:53.380 --> 00:57:55.480 align:middle line:90%
as many directions as points.

00:57:55.480 --> 00:57:58.540 align:middle line:84%
If I draw lines in these
different directions

00:57:58.540 --> 00:58:00.700 align:middle line:84%
through my base point,
most of those lines

00:58:00.700 --> 00:58:02.650 align:middle line:90%
won't hit any other point.

00:58:02.650 --> 00:58:05.030 align:middle line:84%
So when I look at
this projection,

00:58:05.030 --> 00:58:07.840 align:middle line:84%
this will be the
only point over here.

00:58:07.840 --> 00:58:12.070 align:middle line:84%
And so in this situation,
most of the time,

00:58:12.070 --> 00:58:13.990 align:middle line:84%
the points don't land
on top of each other

00:58:13.990 --> 00:58:14.990 align:middle line:90%
when you do projections.

00:58:14.990 --> 00:58:17.080 align:middle line:84%
And so this size
of the projection

00:58:17.080 --> 00:58:19.040 align:middle line:84%
is around the same as
the size of the set.

00:58:19.040 --> 00:58:21.815 align:middle line:90%


00:58:21.815 --> 00:58:22.315 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:22.315 --> 00:58:27.340 align:middle line:90%


00:58:27.340 --> 00:58:28.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:28.660 --> 00:58:29.240 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:58:29.240 --> 00:58:32.080 align:middle line:84%
So now L are all of the lines
that go through X with slope

00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:36.340 align:middle line:84%
in D. And each line only
goes through a small fraction

00:58:36.340 --> 00:58:36.950 align:middle line:90%
of the cells.

00:58:36.950 --> 00:58:48.070 align:middle line:90%


00:58:48.070 --> 00:58:55.430 align:middle line:84%
So Li would be the lines
that go through Oi.

00:58:55.430 --> 00:59:03.130 align:middle line:84%
And for a typical cell, Li would
be smaller than L over sigma.

00:59:03.130 --> 00:59:07.360 align:middle line:84%
So now what we do is
we cut up our picture

00:59:07.360 --> 00:59:10.310 align:middle line:84%
into small enough cells
that in each cell,

00:59:10.310 --> 00:59:12.280 align:middle line:84%
the number of
directions is bigger

00:59:12.280 --> 00:59:13.380 align:middle line:90%
than the number of points.

00:59:13.380 --> 00:59:16.330 align:middle line:90%


00:59:16.330 --> 00:59:22.810 align:middle line:84%
So we choose sigma so that X
over sigma squared is smaller

00:59:22.810 --> 00:59:25.216 align:middle line:84%
than 1/2 of the
number of directions.

00:59:25.216 --> 00:59:30.620 align:middle line:90%


00:59:30.620 --> 00:59:37.100 align:middle line:84%
And so then we get that
Si is bigger than Xi,

00:59:37.100 --> 00:59:38.770 align:middle line:90%
which is X over sigma squared.

00:59:38.770 --> 00:59:44.120 align:middle line:90%


00:59:44.120 --> 00:59:46.000 align:middle line:90%
And from that, we can compute.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:53.682 align:middle line:90%


00:59:53.682 --> 00:59:55.590 align:middle line:90%
So let me say this.

00:59:55.590 --> 01:00:01.010 align:middle line:84%
So S, S times D is
the number of lines.

01:00:01.010 --> 01:00:05.270 align:middle line:84%
And that's bigger than sigma
times the number of lines

01:00:05.270 --> 01:00:09.620 align:middle line:84%
through a typical cell,
which is like sigma times

01:00:09.620 --> 01:00:13.280 align:middle line:84%
the number of directions
times the size of a projection

01:00:13.280 --> 01:00:14.610 align:middle line:90%
for a particular cell.

01:00:14.610 --> 01:00:17.540 align:middle line:84%
So then in each cell,
the number of lines

01:00:17.540 --> 01:00:23.480 align:middle line:84%
is the number of directions
times the size of a projection.

01:00:23.480 --> 01:00:24.304 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:24.304 --> 01:00:28.310 align:middle line:90%
And Si is bigger than Xi.

01:00:28.310 --> 01:00:34.880 align:middle line:84%
So that's bigger than sigma
times D times X over sigma

01:00:34.880 --> 01:00:37.250 align:middle line:90%
squared.

01:00:37.250 --> 01:00:42.410 align:middle line:90%
So that's X times D over sigma.

01:00:42.410 --> 01:00:45.560 align:middle line:90%
And sigma is dictated here.

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:51.140 align:middle line:84%
So if you plug in
the value of sigma,

01:00:51.140 --> 01:00:56.160 align:middle line:84%
you get that this is X
to the 1/2 D to the 3/2,

01:00:56.160 --> 01:00:59.965 align:middle line:84%
and you cancel the D's,
and that's the lower bound.

01:00:59.965 --> 01:01:04.520 align:middle line:90%


01:01:04.520 --> 01:01:05.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:05.020 --> 01:01:09.520 align:middle line:90%


01:01:09.520 --> 01:01:12.110 align:middle line:84%
So algebra aside,
what is happening

01:01:12.110 --> 01:01:14.550 align:middle line:84%
is that we do this
cell decomposition,

01:01:14.550 --> 01:01:18.260 align:middle line:84%
and we cut things up finely
enough so that within this cell,

01:01:18.260 --> 01:01:20.090 align:middle line:84%
the number of
directions is bigger

01:01:20.090 --> 01:01:22.620 align:middle line:84%
than the number of
points in this cell.

01:01:22.620 --> 01:01:26.380 align:middle line:84%
Then we know that a typical line
only goes through one point.

01:01:26.380 --> 01:01:31.020 align:middle line:84%
And then we count everything up,
and Szemerédi-Trotter falls in.

01:01:31.020 --> 01:01:34.910 align:middle line:84%
What goes wrong when we try
to do this for unit balls?

01:01:34.910 --> 01:01:40.980 align:middle line:90%


01:01:40.980 --> 01:01:45.670 align:middle line:84%
So if the set X has an alpha
dimensional spacing condition,

01:01:45.670 --> 01:01:47.460 align:middle line:84%
then you should
visualize it as being

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:48.760 align:middle line:90%
something like a Cantor set.

01:01:48.760 --> 01:01:52.530 align:middle line:90%
So I tried to draw that here.

01:01:52.530 --> 01:01:55.950 align:middle line:90%
So now we can partition it.

01:01:55.950 --> 01:01:57.936 align:middle line:90%
We do our cell decomposition.

01:01:57.936 --> 01:02:00.660 align:middle line:90%


01:02:00.660 --> 01:02:03.390 align:middle line:90%
We have sigma squared cells.

01:02:03.390 --> 01:02:06.600 align:middle line:90%
Sigma is a parameter.

01:02:06.600 --> 01:02:10.510 align:middle line:90%
So Xi is X intersected with Oi.

01:02:10.510 --> 01:02:11.435 align:middle line:90%
So here it is.

01:02:11.435 --> 01:02:14.850 align:middle line:90%


01:02:14.850 --> 01:02:19.140 align:middle line:84%
And well, we'd like to think
of this as a smaller version

01:02:19.140 --> 01:02:21.080 align:middle line:90%
of our original problem.

01:02:21.080 --> 01:02:24.590 align:middle line:84%
And our original problem
was about unit balls

01:02:24.590 --> 01:02:26.460 align:middle line:90%
in a bigger ball.

01:02:26.460 --> 01:02:31.390 align:middle line:84%
So actually, we need to know,
how big is this bigger ball?

01:02:31.390 --> 01:02:33.920 align:middle line:90%


01:02:33.920 --> 01:02:36.110 align:middle line:84%
Let's call it that a
ball of radius little r.

01:02:36.110 --> 01:02:38.610 align:middle line:84%
Now, it won't
necessarily happen.

01:02:38.610 --> 01:02:41.330 align:middle line:84%
We don't know for sure
that Xi is organized

01:02:41.330 --> 01:02:43.380 align:middle line:90%
into one ball like this.

01:02:43.380 --> 01:02:46.920 align:middle line:84%
But that could happen, and
it's the most important case.

01:02:46.920 --> 01:02:49.310 align:middle line:84%
So let's just imagine
that each of these Xi's

01:02:49.310 --> 01:02:50.755 align:middle line:90%
lives in one ball like this.

01:02:50.755 --> 01:02:53.420 align:middle line:90%


01:02:53.420 --> 01:02:54.364 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:54.364 --> 01:02:57.890 align:middle line:84%
Now, we're going to think
of this as a smaller version

01:02:57.890 --> 01:02:59.840 align:middle line:90%
of our original problem.

01:02:59.840 --> 01:03:03.140 align:middle line:84%
In our original problem,
we had a set of directions,

01:03:03.140 --> 01:03:06.950 align:middle line:84%
and we needed them to
be 1 over r separated

01:03:06.950 --> 01:03:10.230 align:middle line:84%
because two directions that
are too close together,

01:03:10.230 --> 01:03:12.590 align:middle line:90%
they look equivalent.

01:03:12.590 --> 01:03:14.970 align:middle line:84%
And now that we have
this smaller ball,

01:03:14.970 --> 01:03:20.120 align:middle line:84%
our set of directions are not
1 over little r separated.

01:03:20.120 --> 01:03:21.530 align:middle line:90%
So here's the key point.

01:03:21.530 --> 01:03:24.982 align:middle line:90%


01:03:24.982 --> 01:03:29.090 align:middle line:84%
Set of directions is
1 over r separated,

01:03:29.090 --> 01:03:32.850 align:middle line:84%
but it is not 1 over
little r separated.

01:03:32.850 --> 01:03:36.980 align:middle line:90%


01:03:36.980 --> 01:03:37.710 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:03:37.710 --> 01:03:41.270 align:middle line:84%
So if you think of it in terms
of the fibers of the projection

01:03:41.270 --> 01:03:44.480 align:middle line:90%
map, you would see some tubes.

01:03:44.480 --> 01:03:47.295 align:middle line:90%
So maybe that.

01:03:47.295 --> 01:03:49.440 align:middle line:84%
Maybe this is one
of our directions.

01:03:49.440 --> 01:03:52.670 align:middle line:84%
And you see that
there's a fiber that's

01:03:52.670 --> 01:03:54.680 align:middle line:84%
a tube with a lot
of points in it.

01:03:54.680 --> 01:04:01.700 align:middle line:84%
And maybe there's another
direction in our projection

01:04:01.700 --> 01:04:05.000 align:middle line:90%
that looks something like that.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:09.060 align:middle line:84%
And this is a different,
noticeably different direction

01:04:09.060 --> 01:04:11.300 align:middle line:84%
if you're looking
at the big ball,

01:04:11.300 --> 01:04:13.880 align:middle line:84%
and it has a different
set of points in it.

01:04:13.880 --> 01:04:17.080 align:middle line:84%
But if you're looking
just within this cell,

01:04:17.080 --> 01:04:20.670 align:middle line:84%
these two tubes or
these two directions

01:04:20.670 --> 01:04:22.360 align:middle line:90%
are indistinguishable.

01:04:22.360 --> 01:04:26.190 align:middle line:90%


01:04:26.190 --> 01:04:27.846 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:27.846 --> 01:04:33.000 align:middle line:84%
So in order to study our
original problem, in order

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:35.080 align:middle line:84%
to study what's going
on within this cell,

01:04:35.080 --> 01:04:37.270 align:middle line:84%
we can't really use all
of these directions.

01:04:37.270 --> 01:04:39.665 align:middle line:84%
We have to use the
inequivalent ones.

01:04:39.665 --> 01:04:42.270 align:middle line:90%


01:04:42.270 --> 01:04:50.230 align:middle line:90%
So Di is let's say D--

01:04:50.230 --> 01:04:57.060 align:middle line:84%
so let's say that theta 1
is equivalent to theta 2

01:04:57.060 --> 01:05:01.230 align:middle line:84%
if theta 1 minus theta
2 is less than 1 over r.

01:05:01.230 --> 01:05:06.727 align:middle line:84%
And then Di is going to
be D up to equivalence.

01:05:06.727 --> 01:05:08.560 align:middle line:84%
This is not exactly an
equivalence relation,

01:05:08.560 --> 01:05:09.390 align:middle line:90%
but anyway.

01:05:09.390 --> 01:05:11.710 align:middle line:84%
We pick a subset
of the directions

01:05:11.710 --> 01:05:15.480 align:middle line:84%
so that there's only one of
them in each 1 over r arc.

01:05:15.480 --> 01:05:18.660 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it's better to say that.

01:05:18.660 --> 01:05:35.760 align:middle line:84%
So we choose Di inside of D so
that Di intersect an arc smaller

01:05:35.760 --> 01:05:42.400 align:middle line:84%
than 1 for each arc gamma in
the circle of length 1 over r.

01:05:42.400 --> 01:05:46.020 align:middle line:90%


01:05:46.020 --> 01:05:48.086 align:middle line:84%
And now we have a smaller
set of directions.

01:05:48.086 --> 01:05:58.740 align:middle line:90%


01:05:58.740 --> 01:05:59.500 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:59.500 --> 01:06:00.573 align:middle line:90%
So double counting.

01:06:00.573 --> 01:06:06.600 align:middle line:90%


01:06:06.600 --> 01:06:12.785 align:middle line:84%
Double counting still
helps, still works well.

01:06:12.785 --> 01:06:15.480 align:middle line:90%


01:06:15.480 --> 01:06:21.545 align:middle line:84%
If it were to happen that
Di was bigger than Xi.

01:06:21.545 --> 01:06:25.590 align:middle line:90%


01:06:25.590 --> 01:06:29.970 align:middle line:84%
That's still true,
just like before.

01:06:29.970 --> 01:06:32.970 align:middle line:84%
But the key difference
between the original problem

01:06:32.970 --> 01:06:37.750 align:middle line:84%
and this version with unit balls
is that in the original problem,

01:06:37.750 --> 01:06:41.520 align:middle line:84%
when we looked at a smaller
piece of it in the cell Oi,

01:06:41.520 --> 01:06:44.280 align:middle line:84%
we had many fewer
points, but we still had

01:06:44.280 --> 01:06:46.432 align:middle line:90%
the same number of directions.

01:06:46.432 --> 01:06:49.140 align:middle line:84%
So if the cell was small enough,
the number of points in the cell

01:06:49.140 --> 01:06:50.980 align:middle line:84%
would drop below the
number of directions,

01:06:50.980 --> 01:06:54.000 align:middle line:84%
and then the double counting
would give a very good bound.

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:57.340 align:middle line:84%
But now, when I go
into a smaller cell,

01:06:57.340 --> 01:07:03.120 align:middle line:84%
I have fewer points, but I
also have fewer directions.

01:07:03.120 --> 01:07:07.823 align:middle line:84%
And so it's not clear whether
I'm making any progress.

01:07:07.823 --> 01:07:09.490 align:middle line:84%
To check whether
you're making progress,

01:07:09.490 --> 01:07:13.860 align:middle line:84%
you have to write down carefully
how these things are changing.

01:07:13.860 --> 01:07:17.290 align:middle line:84%
And I won't do the
whole computation,

01:07:17.290 --> 01:07:19.620 align:middle line:90%
but I'll tell you what happens.

01:07:19.620 --> 01:07:29.950 align:middle line:84%
So if X and D are Hausdorff,
and so X is R to the alpha,

01:07:29.950 --> 01:07:35.460 align:middle line:84%
so X is alpha dimensional,
and D is R to the beta,

01:07:35.460 --> 01:07:38.400 align:middle line:84%
or D is beta dimensional,
then what you'll find

01:07:38.400 --> 01:07:42.600 align:middle line:84%
is that Xi is little
r to the alpha.

01:07:42.600 --> 01:07:44.460 align:middle line:84%
So the radius little
R would depend

01:07:44.460 --> 01:07:46.150 align:middle line:90%
on how much we chop things up.

01:07:46.150 --> 01:07:47.860 align:middle line:84%
If I take a finer
cell decomposition,

01:07:47.860 --> 01:07:49.060 align:middle line:90%
little r will get smaller.

01:07:49.060 --> 01:07:52.110 align:middle line:84%
So it's essentially a free
parameter that I can choose.

01:07:52.110 --> 01:07:54.840 align:middle line:84%
Xi will be like
little r to the alpha,

01:07:54.840 --> 01:07:57.710 align:middle line:84%
and Di will be
little r to the beta.

01:07:57.710 --> 01:08:02.910 align:middle line:90%


01:08:02.910 --> 01:08:06.340 align:middle line:84%
So if alpha was bigger
than beta initially,

01:08:06.340 --> 01:08:08.550 align:middle line:84%
so I had many more points
than directions, which

01:08:08.550 --> 01:08:12.780 align:middle line:84%
is the interesting in case,
after I look at a smaller cell,

01:08:12.780 --> 01:08:14.440 align:middle line:84%
alpha will still be
bigger than beta,

01:08:14.440 --> 01:08:16.496 align:middle line:84%
so I still have many more
points than directions.

01:08:16.496 --> 01:08:19.529 align:middle line:90%


01:08:19.529 --> 01:08:22.200 align:middle line:84%
So I won't ever get
to a place where I

01:08:22.200 --> 01:08:23.614 align:middle line:90%
can apply this double counting.

01:08:23.614 --> 01:08:34.269 align:middle line:90%


01:08:34.269 --> 01:08:35.399 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:35.399 --> 01:08:37.770 align:middle line:84%
Now having said
that, I think there

01:08:37.770 --> 01:08:41.130 align:middle line:84%
are some situations where
this method would give

01:08:41.130 --> 01:08:43.529 align:middle line:90%
something new and interesting.

01:08:43.529 --> 01:08:48.550 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, when
we did this computation,

01:08:48.550 --> 01:08:53.880 align:middle line:84%
it was predicated on
having equalities here.

01:08:53.880 --> 01:08:56.760 align:middle line:84%
And if we had strong
inequalities here, then

01:08:56.760 --> 01:08:59.290 align:middle line:84%
something more
favorable would happen,

01:08:59.290 --> 01:09:04.470 align:middle line:84%
and we might get an
interesting estimate.

01:09:04.470 --> 01:09:07.590 align:middle line:84%
I don't think this has ever
been written down carefully.

01:09:07.590 --> 01:09:10.410 align:middle line:84%
So Tom Wolff tried really
hard to understand this,

01:09:10.410 --> 01:09:12.660 align:middle line:84%
and I'm sure he thought
through everything that I just

01:09:12.660 --> 01:09:13.920 align:middle line:90%
presented.

01:09:13.920 --> 01:09:16.439 align:middle line:84%
But I guess the
answers didn't turn out

01:09:16.439 --> 01:09:20.770 align:middle line:84%
sufficiently positive for him
to write it up as a paper.

01:09:20.770 --> 01:09:23.670 align:middle line:84%
And I don't think anyone else
has really systematically done

01:09:23.670 --> 01:09:24.899 align:middle line:90%
it.

01:09:24.899 --> 01:09:26.580 align:middle line:84%
So also, it could
be a good project

01:09:26.580 --> 01:09:29.179 align:middle line:84%
to see how much does cell
decomposition tell us.

01:09:29.179 --> 01:09:34.920 align:middle line:90%


01:09:34.920 --> 01:09:36.066 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:36.066 --> 01:09:40.680 align:middle line:84%
Now, there is also an example
that's worth mentioning.

01:09:40.680 --> 01:09:46.350 align:middle line:84%
Why being able to cut
things into pieces

01:09:46.350 --> 01:09:48.209 align:middle line:90%
doesn't necessarily let us--

01:09:48.209 --> 01:09:52.060 align:middle line:90%


01:09:52.060 --> 01:09:52.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:52.560 --> 01:09:55.410 align:middle line:84%
So this was, OK, so there's
also an example that

01:09:55.410 --> 01:09:57.180 align:middle line:84%
matches the story that
I was just telling

01:09:57.180 --> 01:09:59.250 align:middle line:90%
about how this proof would go.

01:09:59.250 --> 01:10:01.740 align:middle line:84%
And the example goes
back to the beginning

01:10:01.740 --> 01:10:03.690 align:middle line:84%
of the class when
we were noticing,

01:10:03.690 --> 01:10:06.400 align:middle line:84%
when we were doing projection
theory and finite fields,

01:10:06.400 --> 01:10:09.430 align:middle line:84%
that it makes a difference
whether you have a prime field

01:10:09.430 --> 01:10:11.840 align:middle line:84%
or whether you have a
field with subfields.

01:10:11.840 --> 01:10:16.080 align:middle line:84%
And that is also true for this
problem that's on the board

01:10:16.080 --> 01:10:16.580 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:10:16.580 --> 01:10:18.970 align:middle line:84%
It's different over
the real numbers

01:10:18.970 --> 01:10:22.210 align:middle line:84%
versus the complex numbers,
because the complex numbers

01:10:22.210 --> 01:10:25.690 align:middle line:84%
have a nice subfield,
the real numbers.

01:10:25.690 --> 01:10:27.795 align:middle line:84%
So let me end by
mentioning that example.

01:10:27.795 --> 01:10:39.805 align:middle line:90%


01:10:39.805 --> 01:10:41.680 align:middle line:84%
Actually, are there any
questions or comments

01:10:41.680 --> 01:10:43.935 align:middle line:90%
before I do that last example.

01:10:43.935 --> 01:10:48.220 align:middle line:90%


01:10:48.220 --> 01:10:50.212 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:50.212 --> 01:10:52.520 align:middle line:84%
So to end the class,
I'll mention this example

01:10:52.520 --> 01:10:53.610 align:middle line:90%
over the complex numbers.

01:10:53.610 --> 01:11:13.770 align:middle line:90%


01:11:13.770 --> 01:11:14.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:14.270 --> 01:11:20.560 align:middle line:84%
So in this setup, X
is a set of unit balls

01:11:20.560 --> 01:11:23.925 align:middle line:90%
in the ball of radius R in C2.

01:11:23.925 --> 01:11:29.230 align:middle line:90%


01:11:29.230 --> 01:11:34.820 align:middle line:84%
So, this ball, you can think of
C2 for the moment as being R4.

01:11:34.820 --> 01:11:41.080 align:middle line:84%
So this ball has a volume,
which is like R to the fourth.

01:11:41.080 --> 01:11:44.030 align:middle line:84%
Now we're going to
consider some projections.

01:11:44.030 --> 01:11:48.430 align:middle line:84%
And I think a good way to
write it is pi t of Z1 Z2

01:11:48.430 --> 01:11:52.390 align:middle line:90%
is Z1 plus t Z2.

01:11:52.390 --> 01:11:58.460 align:middle line:84%
So in this story, Z1 and Z2
and t are all complex numbers.

01:11:58.460 --> 01:12:00.950 align:middle line:84%
So these are
complex projections.

01:12:00.950 --> 01:12:03.040 align:middle line:84%
And they're parameterized
by a complex number

01:12:03.040 --> 01:12:06.610 align:middle line:84%
t, which maybe we can think
of as being in the unit ball.

01:12:06.610 --> 01:12:10.750 align:middle line:84%
So D is contained in the
unit ball in the space

01:12:10.750 --> 01:12:13.000 align:middle line:90%
of complex numbers.

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:18.190 align:middle line:90%
And it's 1 over R separated.

01:12:18.190 --> 01:12:18.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:18.950 --> 01:12:29.680 align:middle line:84%
And then we can define SXD and
NXR and ND rho and Hausdorff

01:12:29.680 --> 01:12:32.440 align:middle line:90%
as usual.

01:12:32.440 --> 01:12:35.140 align:middle line:84%
All those definitions translate
in a straightforward way

01:12:35.140 --> 01:12:36.240 align:middle line:90%
to the complex setting.

01:12:36.240 --> 01:12:39.040 align:middle line:90%


01:12:39.040 --> 01:12:42.130 align:middle line:84%
And now the example,
basically, is

01:12:42.130 --> 01:12:46.240 align:middle line:84%
that the set X is basically
R2, the real points,

01:12:46.240 --> 01:12:51.700 align:middle line:84%
and the set of directions are
going to be the real directions.

01:12:51.700 --> 01:13:02.230 align:middle line:84%
So X is a set of unit
balls with centers in R2,

01:13:02.230 --> 01:13:06.070 align:middle line:84%
and they're sitting in the ball
of radius R. So the size of X

01:13:06.070 --> 01:13:09.730 align:middle line:90%
would be like R squared.

01:13:09.730 --> 01:13:12.160 align:middle line:84%
Or R squared kind of
real balls among R

01:13:12.160 --> 01:13:14.770 align:middle line:90%
to the fourth complex balls.

01:13:14.770 --> 01:13:19.120 align:middle line:84%
And our set of
directions is going

01:13:19.120 --> 01:13:22.460 align:middle line:84%
to be contained in the
real part of the ball.

01:13:22.460 --> 01:13:24.320 align:middle line:90%
And they're 1 over R separated.

01:13:24.320 --> 01:13:30.040 align:middle line:84%
So our set of directions
will have size R.

01:13:30.040 --> 01:13:34.750 align:middle line:84%
So now if I take a real
point Z1, Z1 and Z2 are real,

01:13:34.750 --> 01:13:37.040 align:middle line:84%
and I take a real
projection, so t is real,

01:13:37.040 --> 01:13:39.280 align:middle line:90%
then that will be real.

01:13:39.280 --> 01:13:44.350 align:middle line:84%
So all of the projections of
all of the centers of the balls

01:13:44.350 --> 01:13:45.440 align:middle line:90%
will be real.

01:13:45.440 --> 01:13:47.470 align:middle line:84%
The balls are still
complex, so they stick out

01:13:47.470 --> 01:13:50.980 align:middle line:84%
a little bit in the imaginary
direction, but not very much.

01:13:50.980 --> 01:14:01.190 align:middle line:84%
So if t is in D and I take pi
t of X, what does it look like?

01:14:01.190 --> 01:14:02.960 align:middle line:90%
Here's the complex plane.

01:14:02.960 --> 01:14:08.910 align:middle line:84%
Here's a ball of radius R.
And it will look like this.

01:14:08.910 --> 01:14:12.460 align:middle line:90%


01:14:12.460 --> 01:14:15.490 align:middle line:84%
And this height will
only be 1 because this

01:14:15.490 --> 01:14:20.535 align:middle line:84%
will consist of lots of unit
balls whose centers are real.

01:14:20.535 --> 01:14:23.410 align:middle line:90%


01:14:23.410 --> 01:14:32.260 align:middle line:84%
So we can conclude that
S of XD is around R.

01:14:32.260 --> 01:14:33.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:33.060 --> 01:14:36.460 align:middle line:84%
So this example badly
violates this conjecture,

01:14:36.460 --> 01:14:38.650 align:middle line:84%
showing that the
conjecture is not

01:14:38.650 --> 01:14:40.425 align:middle line:90%
true over the complex numbers.

01:14:40.425 --> 01:14:43.090 align:middle line:90%


01:14:43.090 --> 01:14:48.430 align:middle line:84%
And this example, so we had
some simpler things that we did

01:14:48.430 --> 01:14:50.350 align:middle line:84%
know how to prove
over the reals.

01:14:50.350 --> 01:14:52.970 align:middle line:84%
We had double counting and
we had the Fourier method.

01:14:52.970 --> 01:14:54.890 align:middle line:84%
Those work over the
complex numbers.

01:14:54.890 --> 01:14:57.030 align:middle line:84%
And this example is sharp
for both of those things.

01:14:57.030 --> 01:15:00.350 align:middle line:90%


01:15:00.350 --> 01:15:04.530 align:middle line:84%
And in this example,
you do kind of have--

01:15:04.530 --> 01:15:07.580 align:middle line:84%
so you could ask, are
there cell decompositions

01:15:07.580 --> 01:15:09.440 align:middle line:90%
over the complex numbers?

01:15:09.440 --> 01:15:12.620 align:middle line:84%
It is a slightly
tricky question.

01:15:12.620 --> 01:15:15.740 align:middle line:84%
The way we built cell
decompositions did look special

01:15:15.740 --> 01:15:21.260 align:middle line:84%
for the real numbers
because we took a variety,

01:15:21.260 --> 01:15:23.960 align:middle line:84%
the zero set of a
polynomial, and cut it out,

01:15:23.960 --> 01:15:26.370 align:middle line:84%
and that decomposed
space into pieces.

01:15:26.370 --> 01:15:29.250 align:middle line:84%
And here we're working
over the complex numbers.

01:15:29.250 --> 01:15:31.820 align:middle line:84%
If you take the zero set
of a complex polynomial

01:15:31.820 --> 01:15:34.760 align:middle line:84%
and cut it out, it does not
divide space into pieces.

01:15:34.760 --> 01:15:37.770 align:middle line:84%
If you take the zero set of a
real polynomial and cut it out,

01:15:37.770 --> 01:15:39.240 align:middle line:84%
it does divide
space into pieces,

01:15:39.240 --> 01:15:41.120 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't
necessarily interact well

01:15:41.120 --> 01:15:44.750 align:middle line:90%
with complex projections.

01:15:44.750 --> 01:15:48.150 align:middle line:84%
But in spite of that,
there is, with work,

01:15:48.150 --> 01:15:51.560 align:middle line:84%
a decent cell decomposition
theory over C.

01:15:51.560 --> 01:15:53.840 align:middle line:84%
And the main thing is
that it's easy to see

01:15:53.840 --> 01:15:55.680 align:middle line:84%
that for this
particular example,

01:15:55.680 --> 01:15:58.830 align:middle line:84%
you could divide it into
pieces in a nice way by hand,

01:15:58.830 --> 01:16:01.580 align:middle line:84%
and the pieces would have all
the properties of the cell

01:16:01.580 --> 01:16:07.370 align:middle line:84%
decomposition that
you would have in R2.

01:16:07.370 --> 01:16:13.430 align:middle line:84%
So that goes to show that even
though this theorem looks a lot

01:16:13.430 --> 01:16:15.210 align:middle line:84%
like the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem,

01:16:15.210 --> 01:16:17.490 align:middle line:84%
and we have a proof of the
Szemerédi-Trotter theorem,

01:16:17.490 --> 01:16:21.920 align:middle line:84%
we're going to need to approach
this theorem very differently,

01:16:21.920 --> 01:16:28.760 align:middle line:84%
because the cell decomposition
method applies equally well

01:16:28.760 --> 01:16:32.450 align:middle line:84%
to this example, which is
a counterexample to it,

01:16:32.450 --> 01:16:35.930 align:middle line:84%
which does not
match our theorem.

01:16:35.930 --> 01:16:38.010 align:middle line:84%
So to make progress
towards this,

01:16:38.010 --> 01:16:41.600 align:middle line:84%
we have to think about the issue
of whether a field has subfields

01:16:41.600 --> 01:16:44.720 align:middle line:84%
and things like
that, and try to take

01:16:44.720 --> 01:16:50.230 align:middle line:84%
advantage of that to improve the
bounds over something like this.

01:16:50.230 --> 01:16:57.000 align:middle line:90%